<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pre-divorce School Helps Mend Endangered Marriages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A newly opened "pre-divorce"
school in the Chinese capital tries to help estranged couples mend
their broken marriages by providing courses or counseling service.
</P>
<P>
Sociologists have said the school's efforts in saving marriages
are very worthwhile since the rising divorce rate in China,
especially in urban areas, can lead to many social problems,
according to a report in today's "Beijing Youth Daily."
</P>
<P>
The school was opened by the Marriage Registration Office under
the Civil Affairs Bureau of Chongwen District.
</P>
<P>
"We make the last effort to save ruptured marriages," said He
Xuemei, director of the office and one of the founders of the
school. She said divorce results in social problems such as
custody disputes and division of property.
</P>
<P>
The divorce rate in Beijing, whose population is now 12
million, rose to 23.8 percent in 1995, the newspaper quoted
sociologist Chen Yiyun as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It's very worthwhile and urgent to open such agencies to
provide legal and psychological counseling to these couples," said
Chen, a researcher at the Sociology Institute under the Chinese
Academy of Social Science.
</P>
<P>
Students of the school are couples who have applied for
divorce. Teachers are volunteers from the district Trade Union,
the Federations of Women and court system.
</P>
<P>
Among the first eight pairs of graduates, one has withdrawn
their divorce application, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Chen suggested providing scientific knowledge about marriage
and family to the public, and educating engaged couples to be more
aware of their responsibilities for families and children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
