<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Authority Rules Out Dollar's Weakening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS) said Wednesday that the country's economic
fundamentals are strong and it saw no reason for the Singapore
dollar to weaken.
</P>
<P>
"The MAS intervenes in the foreign exchange market from time to
time to iron out short-term fluctuations. We do not publicize our
exchange rate operations," local television quoted the MAS,
Singapore's central bank, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"As Singapore's economic fundamentals remain sound, we see no
reason why the Singapore dollar should weaken," it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore dollar firmed above the 1.68 level to the U.S.
dollar Wednesday, partly on talks that the MAS had intervened
after the Singapore currency fell to a six-year low of 1.717 in
London trading overnight.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said speculation that the MAS had been selling U.S.
dollars again on Wednesday added to the Singapore dollar's gains.
But most agreed that such an operation would have been aimed at
smoothing sharp movements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
