<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 35 People Die in Traffic Accidents in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- At least 35 people were
killed today in two separate car crashes in South Africa, South
African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
At least 25 people were killed when their bus crashed into a
dried riverbed just outside Queenstown in the Eastern Cape
Province early this morning, local police said.
</P>
<P>
The bus apparently left the road and crashed into a deep
riverbed, police said.
</P>
<P>
42 passengers survived the accident, some of whom were
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
It appeared as if most of the passengers were from Gauteng
Province visiting relatives in the former Transkei, according to
the police.
</P>
<P>
In another accident, 10 people died and at least six were
seriously injured in a head-on collision between a minibus taxi
and a truck near Pietermaritzburg this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Pietermaritzburg lies about 75 kilometers northwest of Durban.
</P>
<P>
Traffic police said the truck driver was apparently trying to
overtake another vehicle when it collided with the oncoming
minibus.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents usually peak at the Christmas season when
more people drive long distances to summer resorts.
</P>
<P>
The confirmed road accident toll in South Africa has risen to
226 from December 1 till Tuesday, the National Traffic
Information Center reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
