<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia to Beef up Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO and Russia today
approved their 1998 work program that aims at enhancing the
security of NATO, Russia and all the countries in the
Euro-Atlantic area.
</P>
<P>
The approval was taken at the second NATO-Russia Permanent
Joint Council meeting at foreign ministerial level. The first
such meeting was held on September 26 in New York.
</P>
<P>
The work program sorted out a number of priority issues for
consultations and information exchange between NATO and Russia,
such as measures to promote cooperation, transparency and
confidence, strategy, defense policy, military doctrines of NATO
and Russia, budgets and infrastructure development program, as
well as disarmament, arms control and peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
At a post-meeting press briefing, Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said that Russia-NATO military cooperation will
not be confined within peacekeeping operations but on a more
permanent basis like the NATO-led Combined Joint Task Force
(CJTF).
</P>
<P>
The CJTF is a multinational, multi-service task force
constructed to cope with crises and conflicts triggered off by
nationalism, religion, environment and socio-economy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, a Russian proposal was discussed and approved by
the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council (EAPC) foreign ministers to
forge a disaster-response capability. Russia also proposed to
host next year an exercise of the EAPC-sponsored disaster-response
capability.
</P>
<P>
EAPC now consists of 44 countries in the Euro-Atlantic area
including Russia and Ukraine and most of the former Soviet
republics.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russian foreign ministers today also discussed their
peacekeeping operations in Bosnia and reiterated their
determination to continue their close cooperation under the Dayton
peace accord to help bring peace and security to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers endorsed the conclusions of last week's
Peace Implementation Conference in Bonn and called upon the
parties involved to the peace accord to cooperate fully toward the
fulfilment of their commitments.
</P>
<P>
NATO is consulting non-NATO troop contributors on a possible
military presence in Bosnia beyond June next year when the current
U.N. peacekeeping mandate expires.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's foreign minister meeting of NATO, a consensus
had been reached on politico-military guidance which would in turn
allow NATO military authorities to work out options of the
possible continued military presence in the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
NATO politicians will gauge after the Christmas break the
options ranging from total withdrawal of ground forces to a
deterrent force with different force levels and with different
tasking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
