<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Government Approves National Health Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
Wednesday approved the National Health Policy for the next five
years with emphasis on extending health services to rural areas
and disease prevention.
</P>
<P>
The policy, which is expected to cost 105 billion rupees (about
2.38 billion U.S. dollars), gives priority to the neglected areas
and the poor, Health Minister Makhdoom Jawed Hashmi told a press
conference here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, the government will launch a series of
programs to provide free or cheaper basic medical facilities to
people, control all the preventable diseases and alleviate
poverty, Hashmi said.
</P>
<P>
The programs include poverty eradication, women health and
family planning, tuberculosis prevention, nutrition, vaccine
production and a national health card scheme, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Hashmi said district health authorities comprising government
and private-sector personnel will be set up to look after health
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The private sector will be encouraged to extend health services
to people, he said, adding that a number of hospitals and health
centers will be handed over to the private sector to improve their
performance.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes that the health policy and the programs
will improve the socio-economic conditions of its people, Hashmi
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
