<HEADLINE> Rough Plane Landing Injures Dozens of Canadians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A rough landing by an Air
Canada commuter jet injured dozens of passengers at the
Fredericton Airport early today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 people were taken to the hospital, many of them
with cuts and bruises, and several with broken bones, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The plane was carrying 39 passengers and three crew members
when it downed at midnight local time at the airport of
Fredericton, which is the provincial capital of New Brunswick
province.
</P>
<P>
Eight people remained in hospital, but "none of them seems to
be in serious condition," said Air Canada president Lamar Durrett.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the accident was unclear, the company said.
</P>
<P>
There was a dense fog when the plane landed. Apart from that,
the weather was reported to be good and winds calm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
