<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria to Attract More Investments, Says Zouebi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Prime Minister Mahmoud
Zouebi announced today that Syria will make more efforts to create
appropriate climate to attract domestic, expatriate, Arab and
foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint meeting presidents and secretaries general
of Arab and foreign chambers of commerce, Zouebi promised to take
necessary measures to encourage capitalists to invest in Syria.
</P>
<P>
He said political and social stability in the country ever
since the correction movement in 1970, as well as the prevailing
security and safety, have helped Syrian economy to achieve positive
results.
</P>
<P>
Zouebi pointed out that Syria will endeavour to extend further
facilities to augment and diversify exports, and will ensure the
production of high quality goods with competitive prices that will
enable the flow of Syrian commodities and products into world
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian premier also highlighted the importance of
activating Euro-Arab dialogue in search of formulas that would
enchance economic, trade and technical cooperation that would
serve their common interests.
</P>
<P>
Syria enacted in 1991 an Investment Law aimed at wooing capital
in new investment ventures that would meet the country's needs for
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The number of projects implemented under this law reached 1,494
by the end of 1996 with investments totaling 363 billion Syrian
pound (about 8.4 billion U.S. dollar). These projects have created
over 100,000 job opportunities for the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
