<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy Boycotts Netanyahu-Albright Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy today decided to boycott Thursday's meeting between
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
This was to protest the Cabinet's failure to map out a further
troop redeployment in the West Bank and guidelines for the
impending Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Levy made the decision after today's Cabinet session failed,
for the third time in a week, to make a substantive decision on
the two issues that are to feature the Netanyahu-Albright talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu had invited Levy, a moderate within the rightwing
coalition who favors advancing the peace process, to accompany
him at his meeting with Albright in Paris Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Levy criticized the cabinet for failing to give Netanyahu "any
freedom of movement" in his talks with Albright. He warned that
Netanyahu could not go empty-handed to see Albright.
</P>
<P>
The wide divisions between moderates and hard-liners
incapacitated the government from reaching a final decision on the
redeployment and permanent talks after a series of marathon
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
Levy said earlier that the government should at least decide on
the percentage of the second-stage pullback in order to win
diplomatic points to ease the international isolation.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu will present Albright the Israeli general national
interests when they meet in Paris rather than give a specific
percentage of the second-stage pullback and the areas that Israel
will retain control in the final settlement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's cabinet meeting, Netanyahu stressed that
he would tell Albright the need to preserve the Jewish
settlements in the West Bank and their "breathing space."
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to present Albright a document outlining
the Palestinian National Authority's (PNA's) obligations
unfulfilled under the Note for Record accompanying the Hebron
accord signed last January. At the cabinet meeting, all ministers
were given a draft document of the PNA's obligations, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
A final decision by the cabinet was not expected before
mid-January.
</P>
<P>
The major differences centered on the two maps drawn by
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and the hawkish National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Sharon proposed creating a 10-15 kilometer security zone east
of the Green Line - the 1949 armistice line - to divide Israel and
the Palestinian self-rule areas, and another 20 kilometer zone
along the Jordan Valley. He also called for retaining control over
the water sources and all Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under Sharon's proposal, Israel will maintain control over 70
percent of the West Bank in the final settlement. His plan was
supported by Science Minister Michael Eitan, Agriculture Minister
Rafael Eitan, Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky, and
Transportation Minister Yitzhak Levy.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu, together with David Levy, was reported to favor
the plan proposed by Mordechai, who recommended narrowing the
width of the two security zones to three to six kilometers and
seven to 10 kilometers respectively. Under Mordechai's proposal,
Israel will retain control over 50-55 percent of the territories
of the West Bank in the final settlement.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai and Levy insisted that Israel's holding on to less
territories would help promote the chance of advancing the peace
process. Both favored earlier withdrawal in order to win
diplomatic points for Israel to get out the international
isolation caused by the stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio has said that Netanyahu is gaining understanding
from the United States that he needs more time to delay the
second-stage redeployment until mid-January after winning the
Knesset (Parliament) approval of the 1998 Budget, which is facing
strong opposition from both the ruling and opposition camps due to
massive budgetary cuts.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has to rely on the rightwing parties' support to get
the budget through the Knesset at the end of the month, otherwise
his government will fall. If he pushes hard now for the approval
of the controversial redeployment, the rightists will take
advantage of the budget vote to pressure Netanyahu to cancel it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition Labor party said it believed that
Netanyahu had in fact decided to withdraw troops from 12 percent
of West Bank in the second-phase redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Labor's coordinator of reaction in the Knesset Dalia Itzik
said Netanyahu only refrained from committing himself to any
percentage of the second-phase redeployment at the stage to
prevent rightist hard-liners from voting against the budget.
</P>
<P>
Some settler leaders and the rightwing lawmakers have
threatened to topple the government over the redeployment. But
Labor and the coalition party The Third Way have signed an
agreement to provide security net for the government if it
carries out a serious redeployment in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
