<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Warns of German "Infection" of Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's central bank warned
Wednesday that the serious financial turmoil in Asia could
undermine the economy upswing now underway in Germany.
</P>
<P>
In its December economic report issued Wednesday, the
Bundesbank noted that although the recent Asian financial crisis
has not affected Germany's exports so far, it could pose "an
infection danger" for other countries and thus undermining the
world economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
"This would in turn put a damper on the German export chances,"
said the Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, the Bundesbank saw a positive outlook for
the German economy, mainly thanks to the continued export boom
which is boosted by improved competitiveness of German companies
and a favorable German mark exchange rate against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Germany's exports in the third quarter of
this year expanded by a real 14 percent from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
With imports growing more slowly and the traditional high trade
deficits in the services sector remaining stable, Germany's
current account balance has once again swung back to surpluses
after "virtually uninterrupted deficits since the 1990 German
reunification", the Bundesbank said.
</P>
<P>
Germany's current account surpluses, which include trade both
in goods and services, were 2.3 billion marks (1.3 billion
dollars) in the second quarter and 5.0 billion marks (2.8 billion
dollars) in the third quarter, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It also pointed out that the consistantly declining unit labour
costs in Germany since 1996, combined with the favorable
development of foreign exchange rates, have apparently enabled
German companies to improve their international competitiveness
and regain their lost markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to booming exports, western German factories achieved an
average capacity utilization rate of 86 percent in October, higher
than the 83.3 percent in the United States, 84.7 percent in France
and 77.8 percent in Britain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast to export, Germany's domestic demand still
remains sluggish, resulting from a general consumers' worry about
the security of their jobs, the Bundesbank said. Germany is now
plagued by a post-war record jobless level of about 4.3 million,
or more than 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, while the western German economy continuing to
expand, the economic outlook for the eastern half of the country
remaind bleak, mainly due to its sluggish construction sector and
its minimal share in the country's export boom, the Bundesbank
said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, eastern Germany will face further job cuts while
unemployment in western Germany appears to touch bottom, said the
Bundesbank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves New Loans for Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank
(ADB) has extended loans totalling 78.1 million U.S. dollars to
the Zimbabwe Electricity Supply Authority (ZESA) and the Posts
and Telecommunication Corporation (PTC), ADB said in a statement
today.
</P>
<P>
The 48.06 million U.S. dollars approved for ZESA would help
finance an electrification project in Harare which is expected to
benefit 15,000 new consumers.
</P>
<P>
The project, electricity III project, is meant to ensure
adequate and reliable supply of electrical power to various
sectors of economy in the capital city and promote economic
development as well as improve the quality of people's life.
</P>
<P>
The ADB also approved a loan of 30.04 million dollars to
finance the telecommunications III project in Zimbabwe. The
project formed part of an integrated development and upgrading
program of the PTC, which aims at increasing the availability,
coverage, quality and efficiency of telephone, data services and
television broadcasting in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The project was expected to commence in January next year and
would take two and a half years to complete.
</P>
<P>
The ADB started its operations in Zimbabwe in 1982 and to date
its commitments in the country add up to 698.69 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
