<HEADLINE> Income Gap Widens in U.S.: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The income gap between the
rich and the poor has widened in the United States in recent years
and New York has shown the highest gap among the country's 50
states, the New Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the wealthiest 20 percent of families and the
poorest 20 percent grew over the last decade in 37 states
representing a combined population of 87 percent of the country,
the paper quoted a study report of a Washington-based research
center as saying.
</P>
<P>
The growing U.S. economy has produced vast benefits for the
wealthiest but done little to improve the income of the poorest
and lower middle-income earners, the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities has found.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1996, the top 20 percent of families in New York
State earned an average of 132,399 U.S. dollars a year, against
the 6,787 dollars for the bottom 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 19.5 to 1 ratio, well above the nation's 12.7 to 1, or
117,499 dollars vs. 9,254 dollars, was the largest for any state.
</P>
<P>
New York was the only state whose 20 percent of families
recorded over 50 percent of all the income earned in the state.
</P>
<P>
The report said the statistics are incomplete as it did not
cover salaries surpassing 100,000 dollars and capital gains earned
primarily by those who are fairly well off.
</P>
<P>
The study attributes the widening gap to the increase of
high-end income professions such as those working in the financial
industry, lawyers, doctors and computer people and the decline of
low-skilled jobs like manufacturing and construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
