<HEADLINE> Russia Not Fit for EU Membership: German Institutes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Three leading German economic
research institutes Wednesday ruled out the possibility of a
European Union membership for Russia in the near future, saying
that the country's current economic conditions still keep it far
behind that goal.
</P>
<P>
Whether it is possible for Russia to achieve a medium- or
long-term integration with western Europe would first of all
depend on the country itself, said the institutes in a joint
report issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The assessment by the German institutes came after calls made
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin
for EU consideration of a possible membership for Russia.
</P>
<P>
According to prejections made by the German institutes, the
Russian economy would at best expect a stagnation this year,
mainly due to its failure to achieve major progress in economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The economic outlook for 1998 is a little bit more optimistic
for Russia, with gross domestic product expected to grow by two to
three percent provided that the Asian financial turmoil remain a
temporary phenomenon, said the institutes.
</P>
<P>
But they also suggested that the establishment of a free trade
zone between Russia and the EU "could send an importance signal
for the future integration of Russia in the world economy".
</P>
<P>
The three German institutes are: German Institute for Economic
Research (DIW) in Berlin, the Kiel Institute for World Economy,
and the Institute for Economic Research in Halle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
