<HEADLINE> Mbeki Set to Be Next ANC President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki is set to succeed Nelson Mandela as
president of the ruling African National Congress (ANC) as he
received the unanimous support of the voting delegates at the
party's 50th national conference.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association said today that there had
never been any doubt about his election after he was officially
endorsed as sole candidate for the top job.
</P>
<P>
Other three of the six top posts were also set unopposed.
</P>
<P>
ANC national chairman, Jacob Zuma, will step into Mbeki's
shoes as the party's deputy president after his only competitor,
Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, withdrew from the race.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, she declined a nomination to the post from the
floor.
</P>
<P>
Kgalema Motlanthe, secretary general of the National Union of
Mine Workers, will be the party's secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Mendi Msimang, the outgoing ambassador to London, will be the
treasurer general after his only rival, North-West Premier Popo
Molefe, withdrew, saying that his province did not feel ready to
release him for the new post.
</P>
<P>
There were two nominees for each of the two remaining
positions. Gender Commission Chairperson Thenjiwe Mtintso and ANC
parliament member Mavivi Myakayaka-Manzini, will contest the post
of deputy secretary general, and Sport Minister Steve Tshwete and
National Council of Provinces Chairman Patrick Lekota will fight
for the national chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
Voting for these positions is scheduled to start at 5 p.m.
(1500 GMT) this afternoon and the results will be announced
Thursday morning. 
</P>
