<HEADLINE> Tobacco Sales to Decrease in Zimbabwe This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Lower yields and prices
coupled with higher tax have affected the 1997 grower returns
from tobacco, the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association (ZTA) said today
in its yearly review on tobacco trends.
</P>
<P>
The gross value of sales this year stood at 4.9 billion
Zimbabwe Dollars (about 306 million U.S. dollars), 15 percent
lower than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The five percent levy on both buyers and sellers was estimated
to have cost the industry 497 million Zimbabwe Dollars (31.1
million U.S. dollars) compared with 429 million Zimbabwe Dollars
(about 42.9 U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The period under review also saw a decline of nearly 17
percent in flue-cured exports compared to the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The 1997/98 season indications show that close to 92,000
hectares of tobacco will be planted.
</P>
<P>
With a return to normal yields, 225 million to 230 million
kilograms of crops should be achieved nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is the country's biggest foreign currency earner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
