<HEADLINE> French National Assembly Narrowly Adopts New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The French National Assembly
today narrowly adopted a liberal immigration law prepared by the
Socialist government, with all the Communist deputies abstaining
from the vote and deputies of rightwing opposition voting against.
</P>
<P>
Among the 564 deputies who participated in the voting, 276
voted for, 254 voted against while 34 abstained.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist parliament group and some other leftwing splinter
parties voted for the text, which is also called Chevenement law
in reference to Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement.
Deputies from the Green Party boycotted the vote.
</P>
<P>
The law greatly eases restrictions on immigration and stay in
France by foreigners, imposed by two previous laws adopted under
conservative governments.
</P>
<P>
It will be subjected to examination on January 21 by the Senate
which is dominated by a rightwing majority. 
</P>
