<HEADLINE> Kinshasa Requests Extradition of Former Zairean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The government of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo has applied for the extradition
of three former Zairean generals arrested in South Africa last
Saturday, South African police said today.
</P>
<P>
Investigating officer Thethiwe Ntjana said she had received a
letter earlier today from Congo's embassy in Pretoria, asking for
the generals to be handed over to stand trial in their home
country, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"I had arranged a meeting with embassy officials for today,
but they never showed up," she said.
</P>
<P>
Ntjana said her investigation had to be finalized before a
decision on extradition could be made.
</P>
<P>
The three former generals of Zairean dictator Mobutu Sese Seko
-- Mavua Madima, Kpama Baramoto, and Ngbane Nzimbi -- were
arrested at the Rand Airport near Johannesburg following an
extensive South African investigation into their activities.
</P>
<P>
There are allegations that they planned to overthrow the new
government of President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Ntjana said they were still being held as prohibited persons
and would not appear in a South African court.
</P>
<P>
They were being detained on charges relating to entering the
country with illegal passports.
</P>
<P>
Should the generals be sent back to Kinshasa, so would their
family members, who numbered more than 200, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Baramoto alone has three wives, children and grand
children," she said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Marco Boni confirmed that the
government of Kabila has asked for the generals' return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
