<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Injures Dozens, Cause Heavy Damages in Guam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of injures and heavy
damages were reported in Guam after Typhoon Paka swept through the
island with 280 kph winds before dawn Wednesday local time.
</P>
<P>
Houses, trees, utility poles and glass were flying cross the
whole island when the storm went over Guam. The island's four
major power plants were heavily damaged, leaving most of the its
135,000 residents without electricity.
</P>
<P>
The storm also blew down the equipment that measures wind
speeds for the military's Joint Typhoon Warning Center.
</P>
<P>
A state of emergency was declared and the National Guard was
called out today.
</P>
<P>
Governor Carl Guiterrez estimated that the damage by the
Typhoon, one of the worst in history, at 200 million U.S. dollars.
He asked the White House for a federal disaster declaration.
</P>
<P>
At noon Wednesday, Paka moved away from Guam at 16 kph with
sustained winds of 220 kph.
</P>
<P>
The American Red Cross said at least 1,200 people were in
shelters. The organization planned to send hundreds of volunteers
to assist in the recovery effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
