<HEADLINE> U.S. Judge Orders Former Nazi Guard Deported to Slovakia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal immigration
judge has ordered a former Nazi guard deported from the United
States to his homeland, Slovakia, said reports reaching here from
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
Johann Breyer, 72, a retired tool and die maker, was found once
serving as a guard at Auschwitz and Buchenwald Nazi camps during
World War II, an Associated Press report today quoted the Justice
Department as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Breyer's involvement with the Waffen-SS service made him a
member of a movement hostile to the United States, rendering him
ineligible to emigrate to this country, U.S. Immigration Judge
Craig DeBernardis ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
Breyer admitted in 1991 that he served as an armed perimeter
guard at both camps _ with orders to shoot escaping prisoners _
and escorted slave laborers to work sites.
</P>
<P>
He said he served involuntarily with the Death's Head Battalion
and denied he was a Nazi, adding he never abused prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Breyer was stripped of his citizenship in 1993 and deportation
proceedings were launched in January.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. immigration authorities have stripped 60 former Nazis
of U.S. citizenship, removed 48 from the country while about 300
remain under investigation. Endite


nnnn
01:07 01:08 g # NAB
</P>
</TEXT>
