<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Support for Monarchy Plummets: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The support for the British
monarchy among Canadians has reached an all-time low, according to
a new poll published today.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that 80 percent of Canadians hold little
attachment to the monarchy, and only 18 percent oppose replacing
British Queen Elizabeth with a Canadian head of state.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 41 percent wanted the monarchy abolished outright
and 39 percent were indifferent.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows the lowest support for the monarchy ever
recorded in a poll in Canada, the Ottawa Citizen newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
An Angus Reid poll in early 1996 indicated that Canadians
evenly split on the issue of whether to keep or scrap ties with
the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
It showed that a majority wanted to retain the monarchy outside
the French-speaking Quebec province.
</P>
<P>
The latest poll showed that support in English-speaking Canada
has eroded: 32 percent favor scrapping the monarchy, 45 percent
don't care and only 21 percent support it.
</P>
<P>
In Quebec, a strong 70 percent favor the abolition of the
monarchy, while 18 percent said they are indifferent and only 7
percent still support it.
</P>
<P>
The poll surveyed 1,410 adults across the country between
November 28 and December 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
