<HEADLINE> Mozambican Trade Union Calls for Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's National Trade
Union for Agricultural, Animal Husbandry and Forestry Workers
(SINTAF) has accused the government of inaction when some private
entrepreneurs fail to keep their promises on transferring the
companies.
</P>
<P>
SINTAF have 340 registered enterprises in the country with
over 64,000 workers, 14,000 of whom lost their jobs in the
privatization process.
</P>
<P>
According to the Mozambique News Agency, Eusebio Chivulele,
general secretary for SINTAF revealed here today that about 50
percent of the organization's enterprises could not operate
normally after privatization.
</P>
<P>
The main problem, he said, is the lack of capital and
managerial skills on the part of the new entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Most of the new heads for the enterprises resort to sacking
the workers as a way to solve difficulties facing the companies,
said Chivulele, adding that some even start to sell equipment,
which is in violation of the agreement on enterprise transfer.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to interfere in some enterprises which
are on the verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if no measures are taken by the government in
this regard, SINTAF might organize a peace demonstration and
demand a better explanation from the National Commission for the
Appraisal and Transfer of Enterprises on workers' difficulties as
a result of privatization.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi said Monday in the
parliament that the country's large-scale enterprises will be
privatized by next year.
</P>
<P>
By early this December, 864 out of the total 1,254 enterprises
have been privatised in Mozambique since 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
