<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Iraqi Diplomats Expelled by Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Seven Iraqi diplomats left here
today for home, a week after Jordan made the decision to expel
them in response to Iraq's execution of four Jordanians on charge
of smuggling car parts.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was apparently annoyed by the Iraq's December 8
execution. Officials claimed that Iraq had not informed Jordan on
the trial of the Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
A government statement issued shortly after the execution
insisted that the accused should be punished with only fine or
prison term for what they did, namely, smuggling car parts worth
878 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On December 10, Jordan decided to reduce the number of Iraqi
diplomats in the embassy in Amman from 15 to eight. The seven
diplomats were told to leave in a week.
</P>
<P>
Amid wide accusations from the kingdom, Iraqi Vice President
Yassin Ramadan promised to secure the release of 140 Jordanian
prisoners jailed in Iraq on Jordan's demand.
</P>
<P>
Later, Iraq declared that it commuted the death sentence of the
fifth Jordanian charged of smuggling car spare parts.
</P>
<P>
But on Tuesday, Jordan confirmed that the Iraqi authority on
December 10 executed another Jordanian on charge of murder.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein expressed perplexity over Iraq's contradictory
moves. Speaking at a ceremony today marking the arrival of four
U.S. F-16 jet fighters as aid for the kingdom in Azraq, some 80
kilometers southeast of Amman, the king said he could not
understand the Iraqi authority.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iraq used to be firm allies before and during the
1990-91 Gulf Crisis. But after that, bilateral ties suffered
setbacks as Jordan tried to distance itself from Iraq to end
international alienation.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties hit the lowest level in 1995 when Hussein agreed
to grant asylum to top Iraqi defectors. In 1996, Jordan expelled
three Iraqi diplomats on charge of espionage. The current
expulsion was the second in history.
</P>
<P>
However, the relations picked up recently as Iraq began to
provide the kingdom with more oil at discount prices and kept
increasing the volume of imports from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Iraq piped to Jordan oil worth 625 million dollars this year, a
7 percent increase from 1996, and the two sides have been
discussing ways to increase Iraqi oil supply to the kingdom in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 23 Million Nigerians Threatened by Erosion, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- About 23 million Nigerians, or
roughly 20 percent of the population in the west African country
is now under severe threat of erosion and desert encroachment,
the official News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Adegoke Adegoroye, director-general of the
Federal Environment Protection Agency (FEPA) as saying that about
153,000 square kilometers of land in Nigeria is threatened by
erosion and desert encroachment.
</P>
<P>
This represents about 16.6 percent of Nigeria's land
territory.
</P>
<P>
Adegoroye, who was just back from the U.N. conference on
climatic change in Tokyo, Japan, told reporters in Lagos Tuesday
that Nigeria needs a multi-faceted approach to avert approaching
ecological disaster.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigeria has serious desert encroachment in
the northern part while erosion is now eating up most of its
states in the east.
</P>
<P>
Adegoroye noted that Nigeria has achieved a 60 percent
reduction of lead in gasoline in line with the requirement of the
Montreal Protocol on Ozone Depleting Substances.
</P>
<P>
But he also regretted that 28 percent of gases flared
worldwide was carried out in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Adegoroye called for a comprehensive approach to tackle the
environment problems, rather than placing emphasis on engineering
solutions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
