<HEADLINE> Bahrain, Iran to Restore Ambassadorial Level Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Bahrain and Iran will
soon restore their diplomatic representation to ambassadorial level,
Bahraini Foreign Minister Sheikh Muhammad Bin Mubarak Al-Khalifa
said here today.
</P>
<P>
He was making the remarks in an interview with local
Kuwait News Agency on the sidelines of a ministerial meeting
of the Gulf Cooperation Council states which concluded here
earlier today after completing preparations for the forthcoming
GCC summit in Kuwaiti Bayan Palace.
</P>
<P>
Bahraini government recalled its ambassador from Tehran and
ordered the Iranian ambassador to leave the country in 1996 after
accusing Iran of supporting subversive activities in Bahrain
against the government. Iran denied the charges and said it was
not involved in anti-government unrest in Bahrain which started in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The minister said "we decided to raise to ambassadorial
level the already-existing diplomatic representation between the
two countries."
</P>
<P>
"The latest talks we held with Iran were serious and we
reached agreement on some steps to boost cooperation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the results of the Eighth Summit of the Organization
of Islamic Conference held in Tehran last week "gave a boost to
joint Islamic action."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Foreign Minister of the United Arab Emirates
Rashed Abdullah Al-Nuaimi said here that his country sought
immediate start of negotiations to end the problem of Greater
and Lesser Tunbs and Abu Moussa islands which are occupied
by Iran but also claimed by the UAE.
</P>
<P>
He said "there are new political indications from Iran and
we hope they would be reassuring. We will react to all
these indications and will work on materializing them."
</P>
<P>
The latest summit of the Organization of Islamic Conference
in Tehran reflected an optimism in the UAE and among the GCC
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
All the GCC states, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the UAE, Bahrain,
Qatar and Oman, sent delegations to the meeting in Tehran
which was seen as a favorable chance for pushing forward the
process of improving bilateral ties between the GCC as a
whole on one side and Iran on the other.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations between Iran and the Gulf Arab states
have been warming up since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
Relations with Iran are expected to be one of the most
important issues to be dealt with at the GCC summit to be
held here from 22 to 24 this month. 
</P>
