<HEADLINE> U.S. Judge Orders Cuba to Pay 185 Million U.S.  Dollars for Shootdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal judge today
ordered Cuba to pay nearly 185 million U.S. dollars to the
families of three Americans killed last year when Cuban jets shot
down two small private planes.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King, ruling in a damage
lawsuit filed by the victims' families, said the Cuban government
should pay 49.9 million U.S. dollars in compensatory damages while
its air force should pay 134.7 million U.S. dollars in punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
On February 24, 1996, the three men were shot from the sky by
Cuban fighters. The Cuban government insisted that the planes had
entered the Cuban territorial sky.
</P>
<P>
Following the accident, the U.S. approved the Helms-Burton Law
to tighten its economic and trade blockade against Cuba. 
</P>
