<HEADLINE> Romania Wishes to Join NATO by 2001, EU by 2005,  President Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- President Emil Constantinescu of
Romania said here today that his country wishes to join the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) by the year 2001 and will seek
admission into the European Union (EU) by 2005.
</P>
<P>
"It was a mistake not to include Romania in the first-wave
enlargement of NATO," said Constantinescu one day after NATO
foreign ministers signed documents in Brussels formally inviting
the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland as the first group of
eastern European countries to join the 16-member western military
alliance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference at the end of a visit to Bonn,
Constantinescu said he now expected NATO to start talks on
Romania's membership in 1999 and to admit the country as a full
member in 2001, one year after the presidential elections of the
United States in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Romania has also been excluded from the first group of mainly
eastern European countries with which the EU would begin
membership negotiations early next year.
</P>
<P>
Under a decision made by the EU leaders during their Luxembourg
summit last weekend, Romania and other four nations were placed on
a slower negotiating track to enable them to make further efforts
to meet entry conditions. However, no date has been set for their
membership talks.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu said today that it would take Romania six to
seven years to make the grade for the EU entry, and therefore the
year 2005 could be a "reasonable" date for a final admission of
his country into the EU.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu already met German President Roman Herzog and
Chancellor Helmut Kohl on Tuesday. Both German leaders have
expressed support for Romania's bid to join the NATO and EU.
Constantinescu will continue his German visit in Munich and
Hamburg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
