<HEADLINE> German Telecom Announces Big Cuts in Telephone Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's still state-run telecom
company, the Deutsche Telekom, today announced big cuts in its
telephone charges in preparation for heated private competition
after the liberalization of the country's telecom market from
1998.
</P>
<P>
Under the tariff-reduction package announced by company leader
Ron Sommer today, the Deutsche Telekom would cut its international
phone call charges by up to 45 percent beginning next March.
</P>
<P>
Major cuts would also be made in domestic long-distance calls
lasting more than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"This is only the starting signal for a to-be-continued service
offensive of the Deutsche Telekom," Sommer said, indicating that
the company would offer further tariff reductions as well as
product innovations in the course of next year.
</P>
<P>
The Deutsche Telekom is currently under huge pressure from
private telecom operators which will be allowed to compete with
the state-run company up from January 1 next year when the German
telecom market is due to be finally liberalized.
</P>
<P>
In a relevant development, Germany today also formally
dismantle its 125-year-old ministry for post and
telecommunications as part of the government's deregulation
policy.
</P>
<P>
A new regulatory agency will be created under the German
economics ministry to ensure fair and free competition in the
country's liberalized post and telecom market.
</P>
<P>
"The beginning of a new era for post and telecommunications is
an important and internationally recognized signal that Germany is
setting out for the 21st century," said German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl in a ceremony in Bonn today marking the end of the post and
telecom ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
