<HEADLINE> Egypt to Privatize More, Retain Strategic Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Showing its seriousness towards
privatization, Egypt said today it will speed up the economic
restructuring program by selling at least 56 public sector
companies next year.
</P>
<P>
"I assure you that Egypt is fully committed to the acceleration
of privatization," Egyptian Minister of Public Business Sector
Atef Hohamed Ebeid told reporters today at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The 56 companies in the fields of industry, import and export,
investment and consultancy will be privatized by selling either on
stock markets or to individual investors, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Egypt plans to sell some of state-owned hotels and
tourism facilities valued at 6 billion Egyptian pounds (about 1.76
billion U.S. dollars) in January 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt started its privatization drive in 1991 with the support
of the International Monetary Fund (IMF). Under a 1996 agreement
with the IMF, Egypt pledged to restructure 500 or so of its
state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
So far, 82 out of 314 state-owned companies on the ministry's
list of privatization have either been liquidated or sold to
private sectors and individuals on the stock market, according to
Ebeid.
</P>
<P>
"The (privatization) of the rest is just a matter of time,"
depending on the response of investors and the appetite of the
market, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the Suez Canal and Aswan High Dam are "files
closed" to foreign partners, and made it clear the state will
control the majority of such strategic industries like the oil
sector, pharmaceutical companies and flour mills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
