<HEADLINE> Lagos to Offer Free Treatment of Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaria patients in Lagos, the
largest metropolis of Nigeria, may no longer be worried about their
lack of money for treatment as they will be treated free in state
government hospitals beginning January 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
Blood test for malaria parasites will equally be free, the Nigerian
television authority reported today, quoting state administrator
Mohammed Marwa.
</P>
<P>
Marwa disclosed this while announcing the establishment of Sani
Abacha Center for malaria research here with an aim to discover,
either by its own or by joint efforts, the most effective
treatment for malaria by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
He also announced a take-off grant of one million U.S. Dollars to
the center and a cumulative budgetary provision of at least 10 million
dollars spread evenly over a period of 13 years beginning next year
for the funding of research in the production of malaria vaccine.
</P>
<P>
To support the funding effort, Marwa said tht all contracts entered
into with the state government as from January 1998 would attract a
one-percent levy payable to the center.
</P>
<P>
Malaria has remained the country's number one killer disease, which
is responsible for the death of 200,000-300,000 Nigerian children
annually.
</P>
<P>
The disease was more prevalent in Lagos as a result of its high
population, the administrator noted.
</P>
<P>
The population of Lagos is estimated at around 10 million. Of the
total, about 91 and 90 percent of the urban and rural dwellers are
living below poverty line respectively, a report on the socio-economic
problems of the state revealed.
</P>
<P>
The report, the result of a nine-month study which was submitted to
the state government Tuesday, attributed the poverty trend to
"inadequacy in government policies and programs".
</P>
<P>
The study was initiated to work out the state's long-term
socio-economic development blueprint to guide in the determination of
policy direction and choice of programs to improve the living
conditions of the people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
