<HEADLINE> Kenya Forms Inter-Party Committee for Balanced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- An Inter-Party Committee
(IPC) was formed today to formulate guidelines for the
state-run Kenya Broadcasting Corporation (KBC) on how to allocate
air time to all the registered political parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
The IPC standing committee comprises representatives of
registered political parties, the Electoral Commission and KBC,
according to minutes of a consultative meeting held here today
between the Electoral Commission and representatives of
registered political parties.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, participants raised their views in support of
equitable air time, balanced reporting and allocation of free
air time to all registered political parties in the East African
country.
</P>
<P>
The minutes said that the registered political parties were
requested to appoint a representative each for a meeting to draft
guidelines for the KBC during the electioneering period.
</P>
<P>
Under a new law effective from last month, the KBC is required
to keep a fair balance in covering any presidential,
parliamentary or local government elections, allocate free
air time to registered political parties participating in the
elections to expound their policies.
</P>
<P>
The Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of Information and
Broadcasting appealed at the meeting to all political parties to
have their own public address system as the KBC does not have an
adequate supply.
</P>
<P>
With regard to equal air time, the Permanent Secretary said
that with the registered political parties standing at 24, it
may not be possible to have equal air time but equitable air time.
</P>
</TEXT>
