<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The United State is to deliver
a first batch of three KC-135R tanker aircraft to the Turkish air
force Friday under an military contract between the two countries,
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The remaining four aircraft under the agreement will be
delivered by May 1998, Anatolia said.
</P>
<P>
An official ceremony marking the delivery will be held at the
joint Turkish-American Incirlik Air Base in Adana, southern
Turkey, it added.
</P>
<P>
The total cost for the seven aircraft is around 298 million
U.S. dollars. The maintenance of the aircraft will be undertaken
in Turkey, which is already using two tanker aircraft under a
leasing program.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft can carry out their missions in all weather
conditions and are also able to take off and land on shorter
runways than other aircraft in the same class.
</P>
<P>
Following high-level diplomatic negotiations between the
Turkish and U.S. governments, the tanker aircraft contract was
signed on December 24, 1994. 
