<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's National Army Promises to Guarantee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The national army of Angola
would serve as the cornerstone for the implementing the Lusaka
Peace Protocol to see final peace in the country, a senior
military official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Luis Faceira, Chief of Staff of the Angola Army made the
pledge at a ceremony marking the fifth anniversary of the
founding of the army.
</P>
<P>
Though progress has been made, Faceira said, final peace is
still far away as the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) refuses to carry out some of the articles of
the Lusaka peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The army wishes political obstacles in the peace process will
be removed in order to realize final peace in the country, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about difficulties facing the Angolan army, he said
army soldiers have been troubled by the arrear of their salaries
and insufficient technical and logistic back-ups.
</P>
<P>
The Angola army was founded in 1992 after a multi-party
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
