<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-17 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Nurse Charged of Murder to Face Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A 25-year-old nurse accused of
premediated murder of a patient and attempted killing of 29 others
in a hospital in Alexandria, Egypt's second largest city, will be
tried, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Aida Noureddin Mohamed was arrested in August on suspicion of
murdering patients at a public hospital in Alexandria over a
six-month period. But the nurse denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
She is also accused of stealing toxic medicines which she
administered to the patients under intensive care in the brain and
nerve center where she worked.
</P>
<P>
Police investigations in the past four months have linked the
mysterious deaths of dozens of intensive care unit (ICU) patients
in the hospital to the nurse.
</P>
<P>
Investigations revealed that the accused was seeking revenge on
her ex-lover, a doctor in the same hospital, by killing patients
under his care.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that if convicted by the Criminal Court of
Alexandria, Noureddin could face the death penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
