<HEADLINE> Aziz Denies Experts' Access to Presidential Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz again refused access of U.N. weapons inspectors to
presidential palaces that arms experts doubted as covers for
Iraq's biological and chemical weapon programs.
</P>
<P>
The presidential sites are not related to the business of
disarmament and they are not within the mandate of UNSCOM - the
United Nations Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, Aziz told a press conference this
evening.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue of presidential sites "has been used
specially by the Americans as a pretext to dramatize the
situation" and use that drama in order to prepare a military
aggression against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"They (Americans) know very well that we don't have weapons of
mass destruction, those weapons have been destroyed since 1991,"
said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
They started visiting the sensitive sites in March 1996 and
have made more than one hundred visits to those sites, and still
they say they are not convinced that those sites do not keep
prohibited weapons, said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that Iraq hoped the Security Council will look at the
situation in an "objective and balanced" manner and look into the
lifting of the sanctions, adding that the Security Council should
keep its promise to respect national security, sovereignty and
dignity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.N. chief inspector Richard Butler will report to the
Security Council on Thursday on the outcome of his talks with
Iraqi officials during his four-day visit to Baghdad which ended
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Butler, Aziz had made it clear that the
presidential sites would never be open to U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the crisis is escalating, Aziz said at the
press conference "this depends on what the Americans are going to
do," adding if Americans would escalate the crisis and prepare the
ground for a new aggression, they would be totally isolated.
</P>
<P>
"We are not scared, we are ready to defend our national
security, sovereignty and dignity," said Aziz. 
</P>
