<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Industrialists Warn Britain on Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. manufacturers with large
production sites in Britain have warned that they would reconsider
their investment strategies in Britain if London remained outside
of the European Monetary Union (EMU) indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
This group of American industrialists, who employ some 10,000
people in Britain at more than 30 plants, were quoted by today's
Financial Times as saying if Britain remained outside the single
currency for the foreseeable future, their investments in Europe
would tend to favor countries, which would sign up to the euro.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reason to do so, they noted that the absence of
currency risks in euro countries would make the trading of parts
and finished goods easier.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Rosso, Chairman of Case, the world's big four
tractor makers, said that if Britain failed to join the EMU in the
early stages of next decade, "this would be negative from an
investment point of view."
</P>
<P>
"The temptation would be to favor the euro zone in investment,"
Rosso said.
</P>
<P>
Bill Hudson, Chairman of AMP, the world's biggest electronic
connectors, said the rise in sterling over the past year had
contributed to his company's decision early this year to close
some operations in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Hudson made it clear that the sterling staying outside the
single currency would involve further "risks" to AMP increasing
its British investments.
</P>
<P>
Other American industrialists also expressed similar concerns
and called on the British government to reconsider its EMU policy.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Labor government announced in late October that
Britain would not sign up to the single currency over the next
five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS to Set up Crisis-Prevention Mechanism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- West African leaders today agreed in
principle to set up a permanent mechanism for conflict prevention,
management, resolution and peace keeping in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The leaders therefore directed their Ministers of Foreign Affairs,
Internal Affairs and Defense to examine the modalities for the
establishment of the mechanism.
</P>
<P>
These are the highlights of a one-day extraordinary summit of heads
of state from the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
convened in Lome, capital of Togo.
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary summit was attended by 12 heads of state, with
the absence of the ECOWAS executive chairman, Nigeria's head of state
general Sani Abacha, on ground of ill health.
</P>
<P>
The summit was earlier expected to dwell on the slow pace of peace
process in Sierra Leone and the future of the sub-regional
peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
But neither issue was mentioned in the communique though the summit
was said to be proceeding "very smoothly".
</P>
<P>
However, according to sources, the ECOWAS committee of five will be
meeting next week in Abidjan, Cote D'ivoire in a bid to resolve the
impasse in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The committee, comprising Foreign Ministers from Nigeria, Ghana,
Guinea, Cote D'ivoire and Liberia, is mandated by ECOWAS to deal with
the Sierra Leonean crisis in the wake of the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
Under a peace accord signed in Conakry, Guinea, the military junta
in Sierra Leone is to hand over power to ousted President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah next April.
</P>
<P>
However, agreement has not yet been reached on some major issues
and the peace process in that country seems to be deadlocked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
