<HEADLINE> EU Aid for Italian Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- A southern Italian region
will get 108 million ECU (120.8 million U.S. dollars) from the
European Union for environmental protection and prevention of
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The region of Mezzogiorno has been afflicted with earthquakes,
torrential storms and flooding this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total fund, 60 million ECU (67.1 million dollars) will
be used to consolidate vulnerable land near towns and cities,
regulate water-courses threatening urban areas and safeguard
coasts and port infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Another 48 million ECU (53.7 million dollars) will be used to
deal with critical environmental situations and to drive home the
environmental consciousness to the public.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed particularly at carrying out innovative
and experimental schemes in environmental protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Set on Ban on U.S. Meat Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union may ban
United States imports of fresh meat and poultry on the grounds
that they contain high-level residues of hormone and anti-biotics.
</P>
<P>
EU veterinary inspectors are warning that they will recommand
such a ban unless U.S. authorities improve methods for detecting
"medical products and contaminants" in food from animals.
</P>
<P>
An EU ban on fresh meat would stop tens of millions of dollars
worth of U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
Though the 15-nation union has already halted the import of
hormone-treated beef, it still buys a substantial amount of pork
and poultry from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The threat of the ban, coming less than a week after Washington
restricted imports of European beef and lamb, is expected to
intensify a growing dispute between the EU and the United States
over food safety.
</P>
<P>
An EU spokesman today said that the ban proposal was carried in
a report supposed to be circulated among officials of the EU
member states but it was leaked to the press and had stuffed a
news story published by today's Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
The report, drawn up by four senior inspectors following a
10-day trip to the United States in November, found that there
were serious deficiencies in the U.S. testing program for residues
of anti-biotic, anti-bacterial and other substances in live
animals and animal products.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman did not say whether the level of residues of
hormone and anti-biotics was higher in the United States than in
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the union, has
expressed that it would take into serious account the views of the
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has taken a more cautious approach toward
food safety than the United States, especially since the outbreak
of madcow disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
