<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Russia to Consider Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 18 (Xinhua)-- India and Russia Thursday
agreed to explore the possibility of forming a free trade zone
comprising the two countries and some members of the Commonwealth
of Independent States, said a spokesman of the External Affairs
Ministry here.
</P>
<P>
The decision to go for a preferential area or any other trading
arrangement was made at a two-day meeting of the Indo-Russian
Joint Commission which ended here today. The fourth meeting of the
commission, set up in 1992, was co-chaired by visiting Russian
First Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly Chubais and Indian Finance
Minister P. Chidambaram.
</P>
<P>
An expert group has been set up to look into the possibility of
such a trading arrangement and report back to the joint
commission.
</P>
<P>
Two new sub-groups on biotechnology and on cooperation in
medical services were also set up.
</P>
<P>
A visiting Russian high-level delegation has been preparing an
economic agenda for President Boris Yeltsin's visit to India from
January 19 next year which has been confirmed by the Kremlin, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
India and Russia today also signed an agreement to boost
bilateral trade in electronics and information technology (IT)
sectors. They agreed to constitute an Indo-Russian coordination
council for the certification of electronic and IT products
including software.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to cooperate in civil aviation,
IT and security systems, exchange of trade information, hi-tech
electronic materials and components including microelectric
products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
