<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Demand for Housing Falls Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's demand for housing
fell by 20 percent in 1997, one of the worst years for the
property industry of the country, the Jerusalem Post daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by Israeli Geocartography Institute for
Spatial Analysis shows that the families intending to buy
apartments in the next two years drop to 11 percent of the
respondents, from 14 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-nine percent of the surveyed who have wished to buy a
flat are looking for a 2.5-3-bedroom apartment, while 60 percent
want to spend a sum of money less than 125,000 U.S. dollars on
housing.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Deputy Minister of Construction and Housing Meir Porush
said recently that housing prices plunged by 19 percent during the
first 11 months of 1997 compared to the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the decrease to the slowdown of Israel's economic
growth, declining numbers of new immigrants and a rise of interest
rates paid on mortgages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
