<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Ruling Party's Presidential Nominee Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Election Commissioner
Mukhtar Junejo on Thursday rejected the nomination papers of the
ruling party's presidential candidate Muhammad Rafiq Tarar due to
his alleged remarks against the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
After detailed scrutiny, the chief election commissioner also
rejected the nomination papers of 22 other candidates, leaving
only six candidates in the contest.
</P>
<P>
Giving the reasons for the rejection of two nomination papers,
filed by Senator Rafiq, a candidate from the ruling Pakistan
Muslim League and a former Supreme Court judge, the commissioner
said it was done under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq is disqualified from being a member of Parliament because
he allegedly defamed the judiciary when giving interviews to the
local media in June 1996 and December 1997, said an order issued
by the Election Commission here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The order quoted in detail such objections raised by several
opponents to Rafiq's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
Those who remain in the contest for the presidential slot are
Capt. (Retd) Haleem Siddiqui, the covering candidate of the ruling
Pakistan Muslim League (PML-N), Aftab Shahban Mirani from Pakistan
People's Party, Moulana Muhammad Khan Shirani from Jamiat-e-Ulema,
Khawaja Kutubuddin (PML), and independents Mir Zafarullah Khan
Jamali and Raja Saeeduz Zaman, the order said.
</P>
<P>
Farooq Leghari resigned as president early this month when the
worst-ever constitutional crisis involving Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif and Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah reached its climax.
Leghari refused to sign a reference against Sajjad as required by
the Sharif government.
</P>
<P>
Under the Pakistan Constitution, a new president has to be
elected in 30 days starting from the day the president-in-power's
resignation is accepted by the speaker of the National Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
