<HEADLINE> ANC's Top Six Officials Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAFIKENG, South Africa, December 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
ruling African National Congress (ANC) today completed the
election of its top six officials at its 50th national
conference.
</P>
<P>
ANC Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, as expected, was chosen to
succeed Nelson Mandela as president of the party. ANC National
Chairman Jacob Zuma stepped into Mbeki's shoes as the new deputy
president.
</P>
<P>
The post of secretary general went to Kgalema Motlanthe,
secretary general of National Union of Mineworkers while outgoing
ambassador to London, Mendi Msimang, was elected the new
treasurer general.
</P>
<P>
Nominations for the four posts won unanimous support from the
voting delegates at the conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Lekota, chairman of National Council of Provinces,
defeated Sports Minister Steve Tshwete as the ANC's new national
chairman and, Gender Commission chairman Thenjiwe Mtintso, got
the job of deputy secretary-general after defeating ANC
parliament member Mavivi Myakayaka-Manzini.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the election results had been scheduled
for early this morning, but physical clashes between delegates
slowed down Wednesday night's voting process.
</P>
<P>
The fights were reportedly sparked by disagreement over the
election of the new national chairman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
