<HEADLINE> Kipkosgei Clocks Fast Time in Men's 10,000m </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan middle distance runner
Luke Kipkosgei clocked 27 minutes 29.44 seconds in the men's
10,000-meter race in Melbourne, Australia at the Zatopek Classic
athletics meet on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kipkosgei's time is the ninth-fastest time in the world this
year.
</P>
<P>
His countryman Julius Kiptoo ran 27:30.04 ahead of Robbie
Johnston of New Zealand, 28:07.80.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not really disappointed because I think the rain made the
track a bit slow," Kipkosgei said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, world champion Cathy Freeman who hasn't raced since
August 17, fought off a tough challenge by countrywoman Susan
Andrews over the last 100 meters to win the 400-meter race in
51.67 seconds. 
