<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investors to Build Thermal Power Station in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Sithe Company of the United
States today initialed a contract with Japan's Marubeni Corp. in
Wuhan to jointly build a thermal power station in central China's
Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Located in Puqi, the power station is the first project of its
kind solely owned by overseas investors in the province and is
also the first in China to be installed with home-made electrical
generators.
</P>
<P>
At a cost of 470 million U.S. dollars, the power station will
ultimately have two 300,000-kilowatt, coal-fueled units, the first
of which is expected to go into operation in 2000.
</P>
<P>
One of the key power projects in the province, the station will
help ease energy shortage in the southeast part of the province,
and will provide impetus for the construction of local power grids
and electrified railways.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign companies have the right to operate the power
station for 20 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
