<HEADLINE> Pak Government to File Petition Against Rejection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government led
by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif is likely to file a petition at the
Supreme Court against the rejection of its presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
A source from the Prime Minister's office told Xinhua Thursday
evening that although it has not been confirmed, this (to file a
petition) seems to be the "only option" for the government.
</P>
<P>
Chief Election Commissioner Mukhtar Junejo on Thursday rejected
the nomination papers of Senator Mohammad Rafiq Tarar, who was
nominated as presidential candidate of the ruling Pakistan Muslim
League (PML-N) late Monday, due to his alleged remarks against the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
There has been no formal reactions from the government's side
to the Election Commission's decision.
</P>
<P>
After detailed scrutiny, the chief election commissioner also
rejected the nomination papers of 22 other candidates, leaving
only six candidates in the contest, according to an order issued
by the commission here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Those who remain in the contest for the presidential slot are
Capt.(Retd) Haleem Siddiqui, the covering candidate of the ruling
Pakistan Muslim League (PML-N), Aftab Shahban Mirani from Pakistan
People's Party, Moulana Muhammad Khan Shirani from Jamiat-e-Ulema,
Khawaja Kutubuddin (PML), and independents Mir Zafarullah Khan
Jamali and Raja Saeeduz Zaman, the order said.
</P>
<P>
Giving the reasons for the rejection of the two nomination
papers filed by Rafiq, also a former Supreme Court judge, the
commissioner said it was done under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq is disqualified from being a member of Parliament because
he allegedly defamed the judiciary when giving interviews to the
local media in June 1996 and December 1997 respectively, according
to the Election Commission's order.
</P>
<P>
The order quoted in detail such objections raised by several
opponents to Rafiq's candidature.
</P>
<P>
Farooq Leghari resigned as president early this month when the
worst-ever constitutional crisis involving Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif and Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah reached its climax.
Leghari refused to sign a reference against Sajjad as required by
the Sharif government.
</P>
<P>
Under the Pakistan Constitution, a new president has to be
elected in 30 days starting from the day the president-in-power's
resignation is accepted by the speaker of the National Assembly.
</P>
