<HEADLINE> Seven Climbers Top Summit of Mount Ama Dablam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Seven mountaineers have
successfully conquered the 6,812-meter Mount Ama Dablam via the
Southwest Ridge route without using oxygen, the Nepalese Tourism
Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The seven climbers, including six Americans and one Briton
scaled the mountain in three groups on three separate days.
</P>
<P>
On December 6, Peter Athens, Peter Hackett and Brian Harder
reached the mountain's summit, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, American James M. Williams, 38, and Sherpa
guide Pemba Chhiring Sherpa, 39, repeated the feat on top of Ama
Dablam, it added.
</P>
<P>
On December 12, Americans Sean Sullivan, 29, and Peter Iappas,
49, scaled the peak along with British national Charles Garfield,
38. 
</P>
