<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton has decided that American troops should
stay in Bosnia past their mission's current departure deadline
next June as part of an international peacekeeping force. There
are about 8,000 Americans serving in Bosnia,as part of a NATO-led
force of more than 30,000.
</P>
<P>
-- After another brutal and inconclusive battle within his
cabinet, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu left Israel for a
meeting with Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright in Paris
without a formal proposal on further Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Senior Iraqi officials this week spelled out conditions for
future United Nations inspections of its suspected weapons sites
that would effectively grant experts at the international
organization even less access than in the past, U.N. officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
-- Two U.S. anto manufacturers said Wednesday they will start
building gasoline-powered cars next year that will eliminate 99
percent of smog-producing emissions, if they can get northeastern
states to drop plans requiring zero-emission electric vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese financial markets rose strongly following the
announcement of a cut in income taxes, but economists said that
the plan won't solve Japan's economic woes and that the nation's
problems are far from over.
</P>
<P>
-- South Koreans voted Thursday in presidential elections that
have been overshadowed by the nation's economic crisis. Longtime
dissident Kim Dae Jung is running neck-and-neck with Lee Hoi
Chang, head of a renamed ruling party. Analysts fear an extended
period of uncertainty until the winner takes over on Feb. 25.
</P>
