<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Aid Baltic Cross-border Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
Thursday adopted a program worth 46.9 million ECU (56.8 million
U.S. dollars) for cross-border development in the Baltic region.
</P>
<P>
The program is designed to support European Union (EU) member
states involved and their neighbors of Central and Eastern Europe
in development across borders in Denmark, Germany, Finland and
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Other countries involved are Poland, Estonia, Lithuania,
Latvia, Russia and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The fund is to go to assisting transitional cross-border
planning projects up to 1999, including coastal radio systems,
rescue systems, coastal protection against erosion and development
of thematic tourism, said Monika Wulf-Mathies, the EU commissioner
in charge of regional policy.
</P>
<P>
The importance of this program lay in the fact that it was a
new ground for European structural policy and an important step
towards the integration of Central and Eastern Europe, she said.
</P>
<P>
The money would go into a joint funding pool while a
transitional steering and monitoring committee would decide on
individual projects and be responsible for implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
