<HEADLINE> Press Center to Be Set up for Kenya's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Electoral Commission
today announced that a press center would be set up to serve
local and foreign members of the press covering the December 29
General Election.
</P>
<P>
At a daily briefing, Electoral Commission Chairman Samuel
Kivuitu said that arrangements to set up the center which would
issue special press cards to journalists was at an advanced
stage.
</P>
<P>
He noted that ballot papers for presidential elections had
already been printed in Britain while those for parliamentary and
civic elections would be ready by December 20.
</P>
<P>
All ballot papers will be airlifted from Britain to Nairobi by
December 22, Kivuitu said, adding that once in Nairobi the
Electoral Commission would place them under its security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
With just 10 days to go before the elections, he said that
from December 21, the commission would commence to train its
presiding officers and their deputies, and a few days later the
training of its polling and counting clerks would follow.
</P>
<P>
A total of 27,775 people have been accredited to observe the
December 29 General Election poll with 27,675 persons from eight
locally-based observer groups.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the observers will be from 25 foreign missions and
organizations who had applied and got the nod from the commission
to observe the poll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
