<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3-Percent Rise Predicted for 1998 HK Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's merchandise
exports are expected to grow 3 percent in 1998, slower than the 4
percent estimated for this year, the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the TDC's annual trade outlook, TDC Chief Economist
Edward Leung said Asia's financial crisis and economic downturn
have clouded the prospects for trade growth.
</P>
<P>
However, the total trade picture for Hong Kong will be better
than statistics are able to indicate because many local companies
are involved in offshore trade.
</P>
<P>
"Offshore trade is expected to develop further. So the growth
of total export business managed by Hong Kong companies should be
around one to two percentage points higher than the value increase
 captured by trade statistics," Leung said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the global trading environment, he said the basic
 ingredients for world trade expansion are still intact and the
current hardship is not expected to be long-term.
</P>
<P>
Driven mainly by domestic demand, the U.S. economy is expected
to continue its balanced growth next year while the European Union
 economy will be slightly firmer, with a broader base for trade
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Once financial stability is restored to Asia, Leung predicted,
the region's economies should be able to export their way out of
their present economic straits. High savings rate and the region's
 commitment to trade liberalization will help facilitate their
economic revival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
