<HEADLINE> North China Coal Pier Gets State Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- A 30-million-ton coal pier
at Qinhuangdao Port in north China's Hebei Province began official
operation today.
</P>
<P>
This marks the initial completion of China's huge program of
transporting coal to the south from the coal-rich northern part of
the country.
</P>
<P>
An assessment group, composed of experts and officials from the
State Planning Commission and the Ministry of Communications,
today approved the fourth-phase of the pier project, giving it a
score of "excellent."
</P>
<P>
Trial operation for the pier, which includes two 35,000-ton
berths and one 100,000-ton berth, has gone on for one year,
loading and unloading 8.6 million tons of coal without incident.
</P>
<P>
Work on the project started in April of 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
