<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses US of Pursuing Policy of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Ministry today
issued a statement accusing the United States of pursuing a
policy of foot-dragging in the approval of contracts Iraq has
signed for the import of food, medicine and other humanitarian
needs.
</P>
<P>
The United States had rejected 43 contracts under the first
phase of Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program which ended last June,
and 25 contracts under the second phase of the program which
expired more than one week ago, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement also provided a list of the contracts held
by the U.S. representative in the U.N. Sanctions Committee, of
which most are water treatment equipment, agricultural machines
and spare parts and medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
It called on the U.N. Security Council and the U.N. Sanctions
Committee to respect the letter and spirit of U.N. Resolution 986
and terms of the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal to ensure swift
delivery of humanitarian supplies to Iraqi people hit hard by the
U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"Substantive and concrete facts have been testifying day by
day to U.S. administration's persistence in obstructing the smooth
implementation of the oil-for-food deal and tightening the grip
of the embargo on the people of Iraq," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait can only be lifted when U.N. weapons inspectors verify
that Iraq is free from weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
