<HEADLINE> Albright Talks with Netanyahu in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright held talks with visiting Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu here Thursday on the prospects of
relaunching the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Albright left for London to meet Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
She did not reveal any details about the two-hour talks held in
the Israeli embassy in Paris, which she described as "pleasant."
</P>
<P>
Before the talks, Israeli officials said that Albright would
not obtain from Netanyahu details on the scale of redeployment of
Israeli troops on the West Bank, as the Israeli cabinet is yet to
decide on it.
</P>
<P>
The United States has called on Israel to "concentrate on the
substance of re-deployment" and on three other issues which
Washington considers essential for renewing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The three issues are the freezing of building Jewish
settlements in Palestinian territories, cooperation between
Israeli and Palestinian security officials, and definition of the
final status of the Palestinian territories, including that of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli television said that Israeli could announce in January
a spaced out withdrawal from more than 10 percent of the
Palestinian territory under its control.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian autonomous authorities only control three percent
of the territory in the West Bank, and jointly control 27 percent
with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
