<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3-Percent Rise Predicted for 1998 HK Trade (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Undeterred by the financial turmoil, China will continue to
pursue state enterprise reforms and trade liberalization, Leung
said. "The mainland's economic stability will help cushion the
fall elsewhere in the Asian region," the chief economist said.
</P>
<P>
He advised Hong Kong traders and manufactures to further
increase their added value through improving product quality,
design and customer service, to maintain a competitive edge in a
tougher world market.
</P>
<P>
By sector, Leung predicted that electronics export will remain
healthy, casual wear will continue to do well within the clothing
sector while for toys, higher-end exclusive items will perform
better than lower-end ones. But the export value of watches and
clocks will continue to be down due to worldwide decline in
movement prices.
</P>
<P>
As for Hong Kong's services sector, he said exports of
financial services will continue to be adversely affected by the
region's turmoil, but the outlook will remain steady for trade
supporting services.
</P>
<P>
Exports of the services sector recorded a 5.3-percent increase
in the first half this year but came to a slowdown in the second.
</P>
<P>
"The deterioration in the region's business climate will
inevitably dampen the growth of Hong Kong's financial services,"
he said. "However, enterprises from the Chinese mainland are
likely to continue raising equity capital in Hong Kong, given the
priority attached to reforming the state-owned enterprises."
</P>
<P>
The volume of transshipment cargo will enjoy steady growth,
whereas offshore services trade and certain trade-related business
 services, such as freight forwarding, trade finance and export
insurance, should be able to achieve modest gains, he forecast.
</P>
<P>
Another boost to services export next year is the expected
bottoming-out of the sluggish tourism sector, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise exports this year are expected to generate 1.448
trillion HK dollars (186 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
For the first half of this year, trade in services went up by 5
 percent to 231 billion HK dollars (30 billion
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
