<HEADLINE> Tung Calls Year 1998 Period of Adjustment for HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa Thursday
called the upcoming year a period of adjustment for Hong Kong's
economy after the recent financial turmoil, which has swept some
major economies in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Tung told the Hong Kong Exporters' Association Christmas
luncheon that he shares the view that Hong Kong's economy will be
growing at about 4 percent next year because of the effects of the
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
However, he believes that "when Asian countries rebound, Hong
Kong will rebound faster than anywhere else." "By 1999, there is a
great hope that we will be well on our way back again to a more
normal growth."
</P>
<P>
The chief executive emphasized that the SAR's economic
fundamentals are very strong with huge fiscal reserves and good
financial resources and that the economy in the inland areas
continues to expand in a very orderly manner.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, Hong Kong is a service center, with 84
percent of its gross domestic product coming from the service
sector.
</P>
<P>
"So certainly I feel that after the adjustment next year, (Hong
Kong's) economy will start to grow well," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung also reaffirmed the SAR government's determination to
defend and maintain the 14-year-old peg system between the Hong
Kong dollar and the U.S. dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
