<HEADLINE> Pakistan Calls for Resumption of Talks With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday reiterated
its willingness to resume talks with India, provided that the core
issue of Kashmir is addressed in a "specific, substantial and
comprehensive manner."
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at a weekly briefing, Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmed said Pakistan has already made some proposals to
India for overcoming the procedural bottlenecks in dealing with
outstanding issues, adding, "We are waiting for their response."
</P>
<P>
He said the operation of a mechanism for handling the issues in
a substantial manner has been held up, primarily owing to the
reversal of India's stand on an understanding the two countries
arrived at in Islamabad in June.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed said some progress was made on the question of
substantial talks between the two countries last month when he met
with his Indian counterpart in Male, the Maldives. But the two
sides remain divided on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan wants the core issue of Kashmir to be discussed in a
substantial and specific manner and the procedural hurdles in this
connection to be removed at the earliest, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian government may not be moving forward for the
resumption of the talks because of political uncertainty in the
country, but Pakistan is ready for talks "whatever government is
there."
</P>
<P>
In answer to a question about the settlement of the Afghan
issue, Ahmed said hectic efforts are in progress to explore
possible avenues for having intra-Afghan dialogue for the
establishment of a broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, is willing to cooperate with the United
Nations in evolving the necessary mechanism for an immediate
cease-fire, enforcing an arms embargo and stopping foreign
interference in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He called Pakistan and Iran the two most affected countries,
saying they have agreed to work together to promote intra-Afghan
dialogue, thus enabling Afghan leaders themselves to decide their
future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
