<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Shows Stable Growth in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese economy showed
stable growth in the fields of industrial production, sales and
investment in fixed assets in November, according to the State
Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Its monthly report, issued here today, indicates that
industry's added value grew to 188.4 billion yuan in November,
11.6 percent up over the same month of last year. And the added value
of state-owned enterprises reached 105.6 billion yuan, an increase
of 7.7 percent. The collectively-owned enterprises in the industrial
sector increased by 12.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country has invested 1.2 trillion yuan in fixed assets
during the January-November period, 12.3 percent up over the same
period of 1996. And 18.6 percent of the investment was in the
country's infrastructure, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said that investment during the first 11 months this
year in industry increased by 56.5 percent over the corresponding
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The country's retail sales volume rose 11.7 percent in November
in real terms over the same month last year to 245.5 billion
yuan. The urban retail sales grew to 147.6 billion yuan, up 11.2
percent, and rural retail sales rose to 97.9 billion yuan, up 12.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
In November, the consumer price index rose by 1.1 percent over
the same month of 1996, while the retail price index dropped 0.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's imports and exports in November reached 28.8
billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 14.4 percent over the same
period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
