<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Life-long Banker Confident of HK Financial Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 18 (Xinhua) -- From bottom to top, chairman
of the Hang Seng Bank Lee Quo-wei has seen Hang Seng growing from
a gold trading house to the No. 2 locally incorporated bank in
Hong Kong over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
For half a century, his career and his bank have developed in
tandem with the emergence of Hong Kong as an international banking
center. No others could be in a better position than Lee, now 79,
to witness the ebb and flow of the evolution of Hong Kong's
financial industry.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the Asian currency turmoil, the financial crises
became a topic issue in Lee's interview with Xinhua. "The crises
in the past were unilateral, while the uncertainty now is
multilateral," said Lee, who became chairman of the Stock Exchange
of Hong Kong (SEHK) after the 1987 stock crash.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Hong Kong stock market melted down in 1973 and
1987 both as a result of overheated speculative trading on the
local market, but this time external shocks triggered volatility
despite Hong Kong's sound economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong cannot be immune to the regional instability in an
increasingly integrated financial market, but there is no
fundamental problems in the economy," said Lee.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the local banking industry, the life blood of
Hong Kong's economy, remains healthy and well-capitalized thanks
to banks' conservative management and the authorities' strict
regulation.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) has done very well in
keeping a close watch on the local banks," said the life-long
banker, who started as a bank trainee at the age of 19. In his
memory, Hong Kong had only a two-page bank ordinance in the 1950s,
while now the regional financial center has established an
effective and efficient set of regulatory and monitoring system.
</P>
<P>
Since a minor run on the International Bank of Asia in early
November was repulsed in a day, the HKMA has stepped up its check
on local banks, which are required to report their key statistics on
a daily basis rather than once a week or a month.
</P>
<P>
The capital adequacy ratio for local banks stood impressively
at 17 percent at the end of 1996, far exceeding the eight percent
Basel statutory requirement to be one of the world's highest. High
liquidity levels also make local banks well-prepared for sudden
customer withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
Taking Hang Seng as an example, its capital adequacy ratio
stood at 22.9 percent and the liquidity ratio, at 40.5 percent in
June this year. "The strong capital and liquidity base explains
why we could weather the tough times, " said Lee.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's economic prospect, the Chinese banker
said firmly: "It will depends on how fast China's economy will
grow in the next few years." The eight to nine percent annual GDP
growth in the inland areas will continue to be a powerful engine
to push Hong Kong's economy forward, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
