<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Building Infrastructure for Better Future in HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 18 (Xinhua) -- By bringing a
20-billion-U.S.-dollar international airport into shape, building
up new port facilities and enhancing network of highways and
cross-border links, Hong Kong is laying a solid foundation for its
continued prosperity in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Shrewd Hong Kongers are aware that every single penny spent in
infrastructure is worthy, particularly that invested in one of the
world's largest airport projects at Chek Lap Kok, Lantau Island,
to replace the overcrowded one at Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
When it is commissioned in April 1998 with the first runway put
into operation, the state-of-the-art airport is capable of
meeting ever increasing air traffic demands, with an annual
capacity of 35 million passengers and about 3 million tons of
cargo.
</P>
<P>
The new airport is urgently needed because Kai Tak is already
operating at capacity -- in 1996, over 29.6 million passengers
passed through Kai Tak while some 1.56 million tons of cargo were
handled.
</P>
<P>
Good Progress has been made with the 10 Airport Core Program
(ACP) projects. By mid-1997 eight projects, including highways,
bridges, reclamation, new town and cross-harbor road tunnel, had
been completed on schedule. The 34-kilometer Airport Railway is
planned to be operational in June next year.
</P>
<P>
The grand new airport, starting in early 1990's, represents as
a massive investment in Hong Kong's future, one that will yield
substantial returns in overall economic benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
