<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Pass on Great Wall to Open for Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- An ancient mountain pass which
served as part of Beijing's northern defense will open New Year's
Day to sightseers just like its world-famous neighbor, the
Badaling Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
A five-year-long renovation of Juyong Pass on the northwestern
outskirts of the capital has been completed, a spokesman for the
local tourist administrative department announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Juyong Pass, about 60 kilometers northwest of downtown Beijing,
includes part of the up-and-down wall on rolling hills and an
enclosed complex of military facilities, government offices,
warehouses and temples.
</P>
<P>
"The buildings reproduce the scene of political, military,
cultural and religious activities inside the pass at that time,"
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Like other passes along the 6,700-kilometer-long Great Wall,
Juyong Pass has a strategic location and difficult
access. Ministers of the Board of War, or Defense Ministers, in
the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) considered it the last defense of
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Known in China as "the 10,000-li wall," the Great Wall was
constructed during the Warring States period (475-221 B.C.) and
was expanded until the Ming Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
