<HEADLINE> Roundup: Building Infrastructure for Better Future in HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Besides strengthening Hong Kong's position as a trade and
finance center and a tourist attraction, the ACP projects will
bring other benefits: improved road and rail facilities ease
congestion in West Kowloon and Kwai Tsing areas, and new land is
being provided for community and commercial development.
</P>
<P>
The ACP projects also provide job opportunities, having
generated over 28,000 jobs for local workers during the
construction period. It is estimated that, upon completion, the
new airport and the Airport Railway alone, will create around
15,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Apart from a regional hub of aviation, Hong Kong also ranks
among the world's busiest container ports, handling 13.4 million
twenty-foot equivalent units (TEUs) in 1996, up 7 percent over
1995.
</P>
<P>
Handling containers and other cargoes add significantly to Hong
Kong's economy. Official studies indicate that port-related
industrial and commercial enterprises contribute some 20 percent
to Hong Kong's GDP and employ 600,000 of its workforce.
</P>
<P>
The latest port cargo forecasts by the Port Development Board
predicted, along with the economic development of Hong Kong and
the Chinese inland areas, there would be a demand for Hong Kong to
handle 39 million TEUs per year by 2016, or five TEUs every four
seconds, representing an annual growth of 5.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
