<HEADLINE> Pak Government's Presidential Nominee Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Acting Chief Election
Commissioner Justice Mukhtar Junejo on Thursday rejected the
nomination papers of Rafiq Ahmed Tarar, a nominee of the ruling
Pakistan Muslim League (PML-N) for the office of president.
</P>
<P>
The nomination papers of Rafiq, a former Supreme Court judge
and who was nominated as presidential candidate by the PML (N),
have been rejected on "technical grounds", the official Associated
Press of Pakistan (APP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Of the 29 candidates who filed nomination papers for the
presidential slot, only six remain in the contest, the APP quoted
Election Commission sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
President Farooq Leghari resigned early this month when the
worst-ever constitutional crisis involving Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif and Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah reached its climax.
Leghari refused to sign a reference against Sajjad as required by
the Sharif government.
</P>
<P>
Under the Pakistan Constitution, a new president has to be
elected in 30 days starting from the day the president-in-power's
resignation is accepted by the speaker of the National Assembly.
</P>
