<HEADLINE> Egypt Uses Cyberspace to Expose Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Keeping up with the high-tech,
Egypt has taken its war against Islamic militants to the Internet,
local English weekly Al-Ahram reported today.
</P>
<P>
The State Information Service (SIS) is using cyberspace
technology to expose militant leaders living abroad, whom the
Egyptian government accuses of planning and financing terrorist
acts back home.
</P>
<P>
It has recently added to its Internet web site the names and
pictures of 14 more fugitive terrorists together with some
background information after the massacre in the southern city of
Luxor in November.
</P>
<P>
The attack, claimed by the Gamaa Islamiya and suspected of
foreign masterminding, killed 62 people, including 58 foreign
tourists.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Cairo's call for cooperation from European countries in
combating terrorism, the SIS web site has declared "terrorists do
not recognize any boundaries. The international community is under
an obligation to work collectively to deny such terrorists any
safe haven."
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the idea behind putting the names of the
wanted terrorists on the web site is an attempt to expose them
rather than catch them as the site virtually provides no guidance
of action or hot lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
