<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Building Infrastructure for Better Future in HK (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To cope with the demand, Hong Kong is planning a completely new
container port on Lantau Island with twice the capacity of the
present one at Kwai Chung, which will be operating at full
capacity by the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Building this new port, on a series of artificial islands
stretching southeast from Lantau Island, will be one of the
world's biggest civil engineering projects.
</P>
<P>
The new port is vital, not only for Hong Kong but also for the
Chinese inland areas, as some 70 percent of cargo passing through
Hong Kong is entrepot trade with the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, as south China occupies a prominent slice of entrepot
trade, the natural highway of the Pearl River is being
increasingly used, with more container barges seen on the river.
</P>
<P>
Construction of Hong Kong's first River Trade Terminal (RTT),
specifically designed to handle river cargoes, got under way near
Tuen Mun in north-west "New Territories". The first phase is
operational in 1998.
</P>
<P>
With the return of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1, no
one doubts that trade and economic links between Hong Kong and
south China, in particular, the Pearl River Delta region, will be
further enhanced.
</P>
<P>
But, in parallel with the bilateral economic integration,
cross-border traffic has turned more and more congested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
