<HEADLINE> Turkish Army Chief Hails Ties With Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Chief of General Staff
of the Armed Forces Ismail Hakki Karadayi today hailed the depth
of relations between Ankara and Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Karadayi told reporters after a meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak that the talks have covered many issues of mutual
concern and that his visit has allowed him to convey Turkey's view
to the Egyptian leadership.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish army chief, who arrived here Monday, has held talks
with Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, Defense Minister
Hussein Tantawi and Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces Magdi
Hatata.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of exchanging visits by officials of
both countries to promote bilateral ties and military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries, including Egypt, criticize Turkey for its close
military ties with Israel, which they accuse of damaging peace and
security in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has said that its military cooperation with the Jewish
state is not directed against any other nation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed two defense and military agreements
last year, under which Israel will help modernize Turkey's
warplanes and the troops of the two countries can be trained in
each other's territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
