<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Building Infrastructure for Better Future in HK (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now Connecting Hong Kong and its next-door neighbor, Shenzhen
city, are three roads and one single railway. Combining together
the three road crossing points, Sha Tau Kok, Man Kam To and Lok Ma
Chau, around 24,300 vehicles passed through per day in 1996, 91
percent of them goods vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The Kowloon-Canton Railway (KCR) plays a notable role in
passenger traffic. Some 48 million passengers crossed the border
by rail at Lo Wu in 1996, plus 2 million tons of goods. On
weekends and holidays, the cars are filled with Hong Kongers for a
family reunion on the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
To cater to increased cross links, the transport authority is
considering integrating Hong Kong's network of highways with that
of Guangdong province. An extension of the planned Western
Highway, or Route 10, is being considered to link directly with
the proposed Deep Bay Crossing.
</P>
<P>
Rail traffic will also be more closely integrated. The West
Rail, a new south-north railway starting construction soon, is to
run from the urban area straight to the border. Phase II of the
rail includes a new border crossing at Lok Ma Chau where
passengers will be able to change to an underground rail system
currently planned in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, to meet demands arising from the development of new
towns, it has recently been announced, construction of the Mass
Transit Railway's Tseung Kwan O Extension, the Ma On Shan-Tai Wai
Rail Link and the KCR Extension from Hung Hom to Tsim Sha Tsui
will commence soon for operation early next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
