<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opens Insurance Information Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Insurance Information
Network, a special Web site for Chinese companies on the Internet,
makes it possible to sell policies on-line.
</P>
<P>
The network was jointly established by the China Insurance
Institute and the Weixin Investment Consulting Company to promote
Chinese insurance companies and their services.
</P>
<P>
"This will help improve the information exchange among insurers
in China, and Chinese people's awareness about the importance of
insurance in their lives," said Chen Yuan, deputy governor of the
People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that China's total sales of insurance policies
reached 201 billion yuan between 1991 and 1995 at an annual growth
rate of 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
China resumed operation of insurance companies in 1978, and the
industry has been developing rapidly during the last few years.
</P>
<P>
About 20 Chinese insurance companies, jointly-established
ventures and overseas insurers now are selling 600 kinds of
insurance services in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, China's fledgling insurance industry still has some
defects and shortcomings, such as few channels for sharing
information, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua Insurance (Life) Co., Ltd. reportedly sold the first
insurance policy through the Internet on China's mainland right
after the network opened. The insured, Zhang Sumian, works for the
Beijing Commerce College. She bought her son, a university
student, a life insurance policy valued at 100,000 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
