<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Meets Main Economic Targets For 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has achieved most of its
targets set by the national assembly for 1997, a Vietnamese
minister said here today.
</P>
<P>
The overall food output reached 30.6 million tons, an increase
of 1.4 million tons over last year, Minister for Planning and
Investment Tran Xuan Gia told the local press.
</P>
<P>
While the main industries maintained a growth momentum, the
production capacity of several economic sectors increased
markedly, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports continued growing as the government
stepped up controls on imports, and the inflation rate was low.
</P>
<P>
While the country's scientific, educational and cultural
activities have kept developing, people's living standards have
improved steadily, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
On economic difficulties, the minister pointed out that
"productive quality and economic efficiency are low and
competitiveness of domestic goods is weak".
</P>
<P>
He cautioned about the existence of a number of social
problems, including corruption, fraudulent trade and the
incapability of authorities at different levels.
</P>
<P>
On tasks set for 1998, the minister said the government's will
endeavor to take measures to stabilize the economy and create
favourable conditions for all economic sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
