<HEADLINE> Household Incomes to be Increased by 2002 in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will invest 340
million U.S. dollars to increase its per capita income from 290
dollars now to 500 dollars by 2002, The New Vision reported
today.
</P>
<P>
According to a five-year plan (1997-2002) published Wednesday
by the Ministry of Planning and Economic Development, 70 percent
of the investment will be funded by foreign donors. The money
will be used in research, extension services, infrastructure,
improving access to agricultural credit and the promotion of
agro-based rural enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The plan urged a 38 percent increase of food production from
16.5 million metric tons to 22.8 million tons in the period to
meet demand from increasing population of the country.
</P>
<P>
The plan also expected to increase agricultural exports from
560 million U.S. dollars in the 1996-1997 financial year to 1,240
million dollars in the 2001-2002 financial year.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the main economic sector in Uganda. It would
improve the country's payment balance requirement, said the plan.
</P>
<P>
The plan also blueprinted the development in processing
industries for agricultural products such as coffee, soap, tea,
sugar, cigarette, leather, milk, meat and others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
