<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Floods to Be Expected in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Fresh reports indicated
that the level of water in Jubba river is again rising as the
Deyr rainy season is about to end by the beginning of January
next year.
</P>
<P>
Local aid workers in lower Jubba region said following heavy
rains in the mountain lands of Ethiopia and southern Somalia,
Jubba river is further bursting its banks near the town of
Jamame, about 100 km north of the southern port town of Kismaio.
</P>
<P>
Community elders in Jamame spoke about a fresh evacuation of
the inhabitants in the Jubba Valley in the past two days when
water started to reach new areas. In Jamame town, the waters
from Jubba River have covered one quarter of the already besieged
town, creating uncertainty and forcing the people to flee their
houses before it is late.
</P>
<P>
According to the aid workers, the people of Jamame have
started to flee towards Kismaio by the only open road which is
the coastal line. They would walk at least two days to reach
Kismaio without having adequate food.
</P>
<P>
A Kuwait-based aid agency, Africa Muslims Agency, has just set
up a clinic center in the town of Jamame to deal with the deadly
malaria and diarrhoea caused mainly by the rains.
</P>
<P>
Abdulkarim Hussein Guled, a local worker for the agency said
his agency has distributed 120 tons of rice, sugar, maize, flour
and cooking oil to 2,000 families in Qoryoley and Muddul Barawe
towns of Lower Shabelle.
</P>
<P>
Not only Jubba river is bursting its banks, but Shabelle river
is further wreaking havoc in the area surrounding Ballidogle
Airport. Reports from the town of Wanlewein, 90 km southwest of
the capital, said the inhabitants of eight villages have been
displaced by new waters from Shabelle River.
</P>
<P>
Hodon Moham Hashi, a coordinator for the relief agencies in
Wanlewein, said the International Committee for the Red Cross
(ICRC) has delivered 40 tons of beans, sorghum, cooking oil to
the area early this week.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that cultivation seeds were among the aid
assistance provided by the ICRC. However, she said, the food
supplies are far behind the needs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations World Food Program (WFP) has
sent a convoy of 70 food trucks to the flood affected victims in
the southwestern towns of Baidoa, Burhakaba, Qansahdhere and
Dinsor.
</P>
<P>
The convoy which was carrying a total of 939.6 metric tons of
sorghum and wheat got stuck in the mud just after they passed
Baidoa, however the food reached its destinations late last week.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,700 people are believed to have died in the rain
disasters that hit southern Somalia since October this year and
more than half a million others are made homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
