<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Leader Threatens Partition of Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has threatened to punish the Greek Cypriots with
partition of the island, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Denktash was quoted as saying that "while negotiations were
taking place, the Greek Cypriots could not be punished. What will
be their punishment now? Their punishment will be the island's
Taksim (partition)."
</P>
<P>
He also told the United States to keep out. "What we want from
the USA is not to bother us. That's all we want from it," Denktash
said.
</P>
<P>
Denktash's remarks came in the wake of furious Turkish Cypriot
reaction at the European Union (EU) decision last weekend to open
accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a spokesman from the U.N. Peace-Keeping
Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) today, Denktash canceled a meeting with
U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel which was
originally scheduled for last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
UNFICYP spokesman Waldemar Rokoszewski said Denktash's office
gave no reason as to why the meeting was canceled.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the week, Denktash said inter-communal talks were
dead, and he would no longer discuss the subject of
inter-communal talks with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Denktash walked out of a U.N.-sponsored direct peace talks
between Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides in August due to the
EU's planned accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Both Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot community object to the
EU's decision to start accession talks with Cyprus, insisting that
Cyprus can join the EU only after a political settlement on the
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
