<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Water to Be Diverted into Capital of Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Water of the Yellow River will
be diverted into Hohhot, capital of north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, to tackle the shortages of water.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a water diversion project was approved by the
the State Planning Commission last March and will start in April
next year.
</P>
<P>
The project consists of two parts: a diversion project and a
water treatment project. When completed in 2003, its daily
supplying capacity will be 400,000 cu.m. of water.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.7 billion yuan (204.8 million U.S. dollars)
including 5.44 billion yen of Japanese loans will be used for its
construction.
</P>
<P>
Hohhot, a historic city in north China, covers an area of 60.8
million sq.km. and has a population of 1.3 million. Wool textile,
light and heavy industries in the city have developed rapidly in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
However, the city is facing an increasing water deficiency. It
has reportedly built a daily water supplying capacity of 211,000
cu.m. but the city needs 350,000 cu.m. each day.
</P>
<P>
An estimate says that by 2000, 700,000 cu.m. of water will be
needed daily to satisfy the expanding population and
industrialization of the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
