<HEADLINE> Australian PM: Convention Must Agree on Republic Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard
said Thursday that next February's Constitutional Convention must
agree on the kind of republic Australia would become if it is to
replace the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
"What the convention has got to do above everything else is to
settle on a republican alternative," Howard told SBS television.
</P>
<P>
"We all know what the status quo is, we don't know what the
alternative is. And what I want republicans and non-republicans
alike to do at the convention is to make up their mind what kind
of republic Australia should be if it decides to become a
republic."
</P>
<P>
All the four candidates declared elected to the convention so
far endorse a republic while monarchists said they will not
discuss a republican model at the convention and will only argue
for the retention of the existing system.
</P>
<P>
Both delegates declared elected from the Australian Capital
Territory are from the Australian Republican Movement (ARM). They
will join the two republicans elected yesterday from the Northern
Territory.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, only a handful of votes have been counted in most
states.
</P>
<P>
ARM continues to lead the count in New South Wales, Victoria
and Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
The counting in Victoria saw the position of Australians for a
constitutional monarchy slip marginally while in Western Australia
ARM's big lead was cut slightly.
</P>
<P>
The results of the voting should be declared in South Australia
Friday while those in the remaining states will be announced next
week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
