<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judges Urged to Contribute More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Judges should ensure that
judicial work contributes more to overall social and economic
progress during the country's reform and opening process,
according to Zhu Mingshan, vice-president of the Supreme People's
Court.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the past five years show that the average annual
increase rate for cases adjudicated by people's courts across the
country was 14.73 percent. The average rate for cases concerning
economic disputes grew by 23.36 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
In the future, people's courts will be required to handle even
more social and economic relations cases which tend to be more
complicated, and judicial means will be required to adjust various
relations, said Zhu, adding that courts will face even heavier
tasks in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In an address to a national conference of senior judges from
provincial people's courts, Zhu urged participants to establish a
good image for courts, safeguard social stability and promote
sustainable, rapid and sound economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 18 years since China initiated reform and
opening, the total number of staffers for people's courts at
various levels has grown from less than 100,000 to over
280,000. The courts have handled an average of five million cases
of first instance annually over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also pointed out that the number of judges receiving
improved professional training will be increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
