<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Edge Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
edged higher in fluctuating trade today, with improvements in
resource stocks offsetting falls among major industrials.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index moved one point higher to 2563.1 with
the early expiry of December options being the most important
factor.
</P>
<P>
"The main influence was option expiry. You saw that was the
main activity. You can never really tell if that's bullish or
bearish but it's come out fairly square on the day," Stuart Smith
from Henderson Charlton Jones said.
</P>
<P>
Smith said the mid-year budget review presented by Federal
Treasurer Peter Costello today had little impact on the market.
</P>
<P>
Smith said the strength in resource stocks came as buyers took
advantage of their oversold status, with foreign institutional
interest emerging.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 9.0 points lower at 4400.1,
with newspaper company Fairfax losing nine cents in trade of 15.71
million shares.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank shares fell 46.2 cents, Westpac also
fell five cents while ANZ rose two cents and Commonwealth
increased 13 cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index rose 10 points to 1097.5, with BHP
improving another 14.7 cents, Rio Tinto shares also improved, up
40.4 cents and some other major resources fell.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks surged ahead while the bullion price fell 45 US
cents per ounce to 287.00 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was 335.76 million shares at a
value of 940.04 million Australian dollars (620 million US
dollars), with rises bettering falls 575 to 495.  
</P>
</TEXT>
