<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- United Nations and Western experts inspecting disarmaments in
Iraq have found that the bacteriological arm stocks of Iraq were
ready to serve, in contradiction to the claim by the Iraqi government
that it had unilaterally destroyed these arms. They also found that
the chemical arms program of Iraq had been relaunched very fast.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States and Iraq have again raised their
tones over access by arms inspectors to presidential sites in Iraq,
and the United States ordered the vaccination against anthrax,
a disease of sheep and cattle transmissible to humans, on 150,000
American troops stationed in the Gulf, as Washington is afraid of a
biological arms attack by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
-- It is highly possible that the 32 million South Korean voters
will vote today Kim Dae-jung, the eternal opposition leader and bete
noire of the military regime in 1970s and 1980s. The next resident
of the Blue House presidential palace in Seoul will inherit a
country in full economic crisis and under the joke of financial
austerity.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- South Koreans today will vote the successor of President Kim
Young-sam. However, stunned by the unprecedented economic and
financial rout, they are not interested in a voting which promises
to be the most transparent in the political history of the country.
The effect of the psychological shock of the crisis on the voters is
the big variant in the voting, while the rate of abstention could
attain 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The restructuring of the insurance market of France is
entering an effective phase. The French insurance group Assurances
Generales de France (AGF) will ratify on Friday several operations
to be jointly launched with the Italian group Generali and German
group Allianz. This will result in the increase of the sharing of
the French market by foreign insurance groups from the present 6
percent to 16 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
