<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Women Playing Bigger Role in Social Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Only four years ago, Li Ruilan
was just an ordinary farming woman on the Altay prairie at the
north of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, taking care of her own
family.
</P>
<P>
Today, as the first woman in charge of a small multi-ethnic
village located about 1,000 km from Urumqi -- the regional
capital, Li is doing her best to help all the 200 fellow villagers
get rid of poverty and become well off.
</P>
<P>
In the winter of 1994, Li was elected by fellow villagers as
head of the village, becoming a grass-root official at the most
basic administrative unit recognized by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
After years of hard work led by the mother of two, the per
capita annual income of the village has jumped from less than 800
to 1,200 yuan. Enjoying a better-off life, the villagers cannot
help thinking what a right choice they had made to elect Li Ruilan
as their leader.
</P>
<P>
"On the Altay prairie, it used to be unthinkable to have a
woman as a cadre," said Boqui, a Kazak farmer in the village. "Now
we know that we made a good choice, since she has proved herself
able to lead us to prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Li is by no means an isolated case in northwest China's
Xinjiang inhabited by many ethnic minority people. Xinjiang women
are playing increasingly bigger roles in society. Now, women make
up 42.5 percent of Xinjiang's government-appointed officials,
totalling 260,000, and about 60 percent of county and city
government and Communist Party bodies have female leading
officials.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinfeng, an official in charge of the regional women's
and children's work committee, explained that Xinjiang women have
an increasing awareness of participating in social affairs, thanks
to the improvement in their social status and educational levels.
</P>
<P>
In the region's current people's congress and people's
political consultative conference, women deputies and members
respectively account for 24 percent and 16 percent of the total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
