<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Recover on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
recover on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index rose by 21.9 points to close at 1591.41 points
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the share prices moved higher as continued
firmness in the regional currencies saw investors seek out
"safe-haven" blue chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
The focus was on property stocks which rallied on rumors that
the government might relax the 20 percent cash downpayment
requirement for private property purchases and allow buyers to use
their CPF (Central Provident Fund) savings.
</P>
<P>
The CPF was set up in 1955 to provide financial security for
workers upon retirement or when they are no longer able to work.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased slightly to 197.34 million
units, valued at 372.8 million Singapore dollars (223.23 million
US dollars). Advances overtook declines by 215 to 124, while 267
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Technologies Engineering was the most actively
traded counter as it registered a turnover of 15.53 million units.
It was followed by M Resources which had 14.06 million shares
traded. Rekapac was next with 8.24 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1.3 dollars to finish at 23.4 Singapore
dollars. The United Overseas Bank (UOB) Foreign increased by 1.2
dollars to end at 10.8 Singapore dollars. The Overseas Chinese
Banking Corporation (OCBC) Foreign grew by 70 cents to close at
10.4 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, City Developments Warrant98 was the biggest
loser as it declined by 85 cents to end at 5.05 Singapore dollars.
Creative 50 lost 70 cents to close at 32.8 Singapore dollars,
while BerLand fell by 41 cents to finish at 1.2 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
