<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Avocado Industry Faces Mexican Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Growers of avocado in
California have felt the pressure from their Mexican counterparts
as harvesting began this week.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 percent of the U.S. avocado market sources are from
California, where more than 57,000 acres of land are devoted to
the dark green pear-shaped fruit. San Diego County, in southern
California bordering Mexico, alone produces 40 percent of the
country's avocado or 140 million pounds a year.
</P>
<P>
Although avocado acreage has dropped 24 percent over the past
decade in California, it still generated an income of 259 million
dollars this year as compared with 203 million in 1987.
</P>
<P>
California farmers often have the capability of setting prices
themselves thanks to their virtual monopoly over the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation began to change since last month. For
the first time in 83 years, Mexico was permitted to market its
avocados in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
After heavy lobbying from the California avocado industry, the
Mexican imports are limited to a test market of 19 states in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican farmers, armed with the North American Free Trade
Agreement, have been pushing to expand the territory. They
harvested 1.7 billion pounds of avocados this year, while
California produced 340 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
Although it would take some time for Mexican exports to expand
market shares, they have already presented a competitive threat to
San Diego County.
</P>
<P>
California farmers are in an inferior position in the
competition with their Mexican counterparts because of their
higher cost of labor and water.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Mexican farmers do not have to pay minimum wages,
workers' compensation and unemployment insurance as the
Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
