<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier, Mideast Leaders to Confer on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen will discuss the Middle East peace
process with leaders in the Middle East in an effort to promote
peace and development in the region, according to Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Tang Guoqiang today.
</P>
<P>
Tang responded to a question during today's regular news
conference by noting that China has good relations with countries
in the Middle East. China, a permanent member of UN Security
Council, has long been concerned with peace in the region and made
unremitting efforts to promote the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said China is deeply concerned about the stalled peace
process and noted that neither Arab countries nor Israel will
benefit from the continuing deadlock which is further complicating
the regional situation.
</P>
<P>
The international community should extend greater efforts to
promote peace and advance the Middle East peace process, according
to Tang.
</P>
<P>
Qian will also hold wide-ranging intensive talks with leaders
of Mideast countries on further developing relations between China
and these countries in order to deepen mutual understanding and
friendship, and increase cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Qian left Beijing for the Middle East earlier today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
