<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Set up Make-shift Clinics to Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Four emergency clinics are
being established around Kampala to fight cholera that claimed 23
people so far, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Lawrence Kaggwa, the director of State Mulago Hospital which
is the most prestigious one in Kampala, told "The New Vision"
that the make-shift clinics in tents are set up in Mulago, Banda,
Ggaba and Ndeeba areas in the city where the situation is most
serious.
</P>
<P>
The number of the registered suspected cholera cases is 192 in
the capital and its adjacent areas, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Kaggwa said an arrangement was worked out by Health Ministry
of Uganda, World Health Organization (WHO), the French Medecens
Sans Frontieres (Doctors Without Frontiers), the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) and the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Under the arrangement, the monitoring clinics are established
near the scene of outbreak of cholera.
</P>
<P>
Mulago Hospital had received 100 patients by yesterday, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Mayombwe, a medical officer in Kampala District, said
the local authorities have spent on each patient about 150,000
Ugandan Shillings (some 150 U.S. Dollars). The situation is under
control, he added.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic has already spread to central Mpigi and Luwero
districts. An earlier report said the epidemic also appeared in
eastern Mbale and Kapchorwa Districts.
</P>
<P>
And 23 people so far have been killed by the disease, which
was caused by contaminated water sources in the wake of rains in
recent weeks. Earlier reports said floods destroyed drainages in
the city of Kampala. 
</P>
</TEXT>
