<HEADLINE> Agro-technology Boosts Development in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Heilongjiang Reclamation
Area, the largest of its kind in China with 103 state farms, has
earned three billion yuan over the past six years by applying
modern agricultural technology.
</P>
<P>
The area, also known as "Beidahuang" (vast wasteland in the
north), is located in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province. The
former wilderness is currently one of the country's most important
production bases for grain and other farm produce.
</P>
<P>
The widespread use of 144 new techniques has enabled local
farmers to increase the per unit grain output, with the per
hectare output of soybeans growing from less than 1,500 kg to
1,950 kg.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of new technology has been a major factor
contributing to the development of the agriculture.
</P>
<P>
This year's total production of grain and soybeans is expected
to hit 8.5 billion kg, a dramatic 3.5 billion kg rise over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The government has backed cultivation programs in the area, one
of the nation's largest plains, since they started some 50 years
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
