<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Continues to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
continued to show signs of improvement today, consolidating gains
at the 66.00 US cent level.
</P>
<P>
In subdued trading, the currency was unable to push above
resistance at 66.25 US cents but did retain its positive tone.
</P>
<P>
It settled at 66.07 US cents, up from yesterday's close of
65.77.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia manager Paul Macarounas said the
Australian dollar had received a boost in afternoon trade. The
strengthening in the local currency occurred at the same time as
the release of the federal government's mid-term economic review.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the mid-year economic and fiscal outlook, Federal
Treasurer Peter Costello said the forecast Commonwealth 1997-98
underlying budget deficit had been revised to 2.746 billion
Australian dollars (1.81 billion US dollars) from 3.807 billion
Australian dollars (2.5 billion US dollars) in the May budget
papers.
</P>
<P>
The review also maintained that Australia's average gross
domestic product would increase 3.75 percent in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar had started the session higher, buoyed by
a degree of optimism following Japan's announcement of a rescue
package to prop up its ailing economy but some traders suggested
caution.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese tax announcement surprised the market and
strengthened the yen." Macquarie Bank foreign exchange manager
Mark O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
"But it doesn't readdress everything - bigger picture, nothing
has really changed. There are still problems in Asia," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended at 84.15 yen
from 83.74 previously and at 1.1719 marks, from 1.1661.  
</P>
</TEXT>
