<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Making Progress in CD Copyright Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Now it is difficult to find
pirated CD and VCD makers in China, a State Copyright
Administration spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the closing down of at least 50 illegal
production lines since last year, he said, adding the country has
confiscated several million smuggled CDs and VCDs this year.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamental way to curb piracy is to encourage factories
to churn out more products welcomed by the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
To meet the needs of the people, China has since October
reopened 15 closed-down production lines. And the country has
planned to create three CD and VCD conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
Camcorders are now commonplace in urban homes, and half the
world's sales volume of VCD machines are sold to the Chinese. The
lack of quality, cheap CDs and VCDs is the main reason why
copyright infringement is so out of control.
</P>
<P>
China in the first half of the year opened its first state-run
chain of stores that lease audio and video products and it plans
to set up at least 60,000 shops in the chain.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture has also opened wholesale markets in
some large cities as a move to limit copyright violations usually
done by private business people.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that things are better for the audio and
video industry, and foreigners have more opportunities to enter
the Chinese market. Companies from the US, Britain and Japan
attended an international audio and video fair last
August in Beijing, and Warner Bros has agreed to allow a Chinese
VCD company to re-produce its Oscar winning films and to sell them
on the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
However, Chinese CD and VCD producers should make an effort to
increase output, improve quality and lower prices, he said, adding
that the government's main target next year will be CD and VCD
smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR Detains Two Bosnian Croat War Crime Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The NATO-led multinational
Stabilization Force (SFOR) detained two Bosnian Croat war crime
suspects earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The duo, identified as Vlatko Kupreskic and Anto Furundzija,
were detained in central Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Kupreskic, indicted by the International Criminal Tribunal for
former Yugoslavia for a 1993 massacre in which women, children and
old people were killed, was wounded during the capture as he
returned fire with an automatic weapon, according to NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
NATO chief Javier Solana announced the SFOR move by saying that
the action was taken in accordance with SFOR's mandate which
authorizes it to detain such persons when encountered in the
course of its duties.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR mandate, the NATO chief added, was given by the North
Atlantic Council, NATO's executive agency, under authority
contained in the relevant United Nations Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"As has been the case throughout the IFOR and SFOR missions, we
will not tolerate any behavior by any party contrary to the
(Dayton) peace agreement," said Solana. "As confirmed this week by
NATO foreign ministers, SFOR will continue its firm and
even-handed approach to implementing its mandate and supporting
civil implementation."
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers endorsed during their Tuesday's meeting
the conclusions of NATO defense ministers of keeping SFOR at its
current force levels in Bosnia until next June to further
implement the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers argued that peace and the civil
implementation to uphold it are still fragile in
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Solana said, "This action by SFOR stands as a warning to all
those indicted for war crimes who are still at large that they,
too, will be held accountable."
</P>
<P>
"They should take steps immediately to surrender themselves
voluntarily to the International Criminal Tribunal for former
Yugoslavia," Solana added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
