<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Launches Guangxi Project to Help Rural Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) will participate in an integrated and participatory
project to help 4,500 poor families in south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region to overcome poverty, according to a UNDP
official in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP will provide 1.5 million US dollars in grant, with
autonomous regional and county governments set to provide 4.72
million yuan as part of the governmental contribution program and
396,000 US dollars as part of government cost-sharing to support
the project implementation.
</P>
<P>
Targeted households, with approximately 22,500 people in total,
will be selected from five poor counties in the region, namely
Dahua, Debao, Duan, Longlin and Tianlin counties. These five
counties have high proportions of minority populations and are
poor, with the current annual net per-capita income of the farmers
ranging between 200-400 yuan only.
</P>
<P>
The targeted households will receive in-kind productive inputs
and technical training and services from the project for
income-generating activities.
</P>
<P>
The project will help increase the average annual net
per-capita income in targeted areas to reach 1,000-2,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The project will also integrate social development dimensions
to improve the living conditions of the farmers in a sustainable
manner. Technicians, teachers and medical personnel will provide
farmers from targeted households, especially women, with training
in functional literacy and basic health care.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, various other training activities will be carried out
in the project to strengthen the capacity of autonomous regional
and county level staff members managing poverty alleviation
programs or projects. From a long-term point of view, other poor
farmers in the region will benefit from demonstrations,
dissemination and replication of the project.
</P>
<P>
The project will run three years through the year 2000. The
China International Center for Economic and Technical Exchanges
will serve as the Executing Agency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
