<HEADLINE> Iran, Russia Ink Memo on Security Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Interior ministers of Iran
and Russia Wednesday night signed a memorandum of understanding
to promote security cooperation between the two neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed by visiting Russian Deputy Prime
Minister and Interior Minister Anatoly Kulikov and his Iranian
counterpart Abdollah Nouri, the Iranian official news agency IRNA
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nouri said that the memorandum would help the two countries
cooperate in investigating crimes and fighting arms and drugs
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
He said that it would also open the way for Iran and
Russia to expand their cooperation in the areas of security
for either country's citizens, safety of road transportation,
fight against smugglers of the cultural commodities and ancient
objects, and exchange of know-how and technical assistance
concerning crime investigation.
</P>
<P>
Kulikov said that Tehran and Moscow should enhance their
cooperation to deal with issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
He also underlined the necessity for the two countries to
continue their cooperation to put an end to the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kulikov, who arrived here Tuesday for a three-day official
visit, held a meeting with Iranian First Vice President Hassan
Habibi Wednesday on bilateral relations and regional and
international issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
