<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rains in Tanzania Wreak Havoc on Major Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 18 (Xinhua ) -- Lasting rains have
damaged roads and bridges in various parts of Tanzania, adversely
affecting traffic during the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Roads in the Ministry of Works, Humphrey Urio,
told a press conference in Dar es Salaam Wednesday that 632
kilometers of roads have been damaged by rains.
</P>
<P>
Urio said 250 kilometers of highways and 208 regional roads
are currently impassable, adding that 174 kilometers of highways
are passable with difficulties, according to press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The government is not in a position to repair the damaged
roads and bridges and is only putting up a temporary bridge over
Msimba River to connect Morogoro and Iringa regions. Construction
of the bridge will take between 10 and 15 days to complete, he
said.
</P>
<P>
At present, almost the whole country is inaccessible, he said,
adding that the ministry is looking for ways to improve the
deteriorating communication network.
</P>
<P>
He said roads such as Dodoma-Mwanza, Nangurukuru-Mandawa,
Sumbawanga-Tabora and those in the regions of Coast, Mwanza and
Arusha have been damaged.
</P>
<P>
Urio said the ministry is making emergency repairs on some of
the damaged roads including construction of Bailey bridges.
</P>
<P>
The government has also initiated a program to pull out all
vehicles stuck in mud along the affected roads which are causing
long queues.
</P>
<P>
The director, however, said it is not immediately known how
much money is required for the exercise as they are still
collecting data on the damages.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, regional engineers had been directed to use
available funds for the emergency repairs in their respective
areas.
</P>
<P>
Despite the unexpected rains caused by El Nino weather
phenomenon this year, Urio said human activities, especially
construction of houses and agricultural activities on hills, can
also be attributed to the damages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
