<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprise Groups Playing Bigger Role In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Enterprises with different forms
of ownership in east China's Shandong Province have formed several
hundred industrial enterprise groups this year to increase their
economic strength.
</P>
<P>
They have combined assets of 100 billion yuan and pre-tax
profits that account for a fifth of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
The Linghua Group, a township-run gourmet powder company
started in 1980 with 80,000 yuan, and has now acquired and
purchased eight medium-sized state-run enterprises with combined
assets of 280 million yuan. Further expansion and reorganization
have raised the group's annual production capacity to 80,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The China Light Motorcycles Group is now controlling six
different companies with total assets of six billion yuan, after
having set up joint ventures through mergers, acquisition and
other forms of co-operation. It produced 1.45 million motorcycles
and earned 835 million in pre-tax profits last year, making it the
largest motorcycle manufacturer in China.
</P>
<P>
Forms of mixed ownership have helped change the economic
structure of Shandong, improving overall economic performance,
according to one provincial government official. In the first
three quarters of this year, industrial output of enterprises at
or above the township level increased by 15.6 percent to 406.7
billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
