<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PBOC Releases "China Bank IC Card Standards" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China
(PBOC) today released Version 1.0 of the China Bank IC (Integrated
Circuit) Card Standards, jointly developed by domestic commercial
banks led by the PBOC, and Visa International.
</P>
<P>
The Standards, the first of its kind in Asia, was formulated by
a central bank and has reached world advanced level, and will
provide detailed guidelines for the development and implementation
of chip-based payment cards in China.
</P>
<P>
"The release of the China Bank IC Card Standards is a major
achievement of China's Golden Card Project. The introduction marks
a new phase of China's bank card industry," according to Shang
Fulin, deputy governor of the PBOC.
</P>
<P>
"The Standards will lay a technical foundation for the
interoperability of IC cards and sharing of infrastructure. They
will also enhance management of and provide guidelines for the IC
card industry in China.
</P>
<P>
"This will propel the development of new bank services, open up
a new market for relevant domestic industries and accelerate the
development of related national industries," said Shang.
</P>
<P>
According to Raymond Chan, executive vice-president and general
manager for China and nearby areas, Visa International, the
Standards marks a milestone in the development of China's card
industry. "It will play a pivotal role in China's efforts to join
the international payment system and the ranks of countries with
highly advanced financial systems," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PBOC Releases "China Bank IC Card Standards" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chan said Visa's commitment to the development of China's card
payment industry has been unwavering. "After the release of the
China Bank IC Card Standards, Visa International will continue to
work closely with the PBOC and our members to support China's
efforts to modernize its electronic payment system," he said.
</P>
<P>
The China Bank IC Card Standards establishes a platform to suit
the specific needs of IC cards issued in China. The 1.0 Version of
the China Bank IC Card Standards includes detailed specifications
for basic IC card payment applications and accessibility for other
non-payment applications. Specifications for IC card terminals are
scheduled for completion in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of China issued its first IC cards in 1995, with
domestic banks having since issued approximately two million
cards. The Hainan Branch of the PBOC, Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China, Agricultural Bank of China, China Construction Bank
and Shanghai Pudong Development Bank have all initiated their own
IC card projects on an experimental basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
