<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Fog Slowed down Pace of Beijing-Tianjin Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Visitors to Beijing's
Tian'anmen Square viewed the imposing Tiananmen Rostrum as if it
were a misty "castle in the air" early this morning, as the city
was enveloped in this winter's heaviest fog.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing International Airport, the Beijing-Shijiazhuang
Expressway, and the Beijing-Tianjin-Tanggu Expressway were closed
temporarily because of the fog, which began to descend on most of
Beijing Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
An Air China official said that there were no flights in or out
of the International Airport from 8:00 PM yesterday to 10:00 AM
today. A total of 120 flights were suspended and nearly 10,000
passengers stranded. Most of them stayed in hotels arranged by the
airport.
</P>
<P>
In downtown areas this morning, traffic slowed to a snail's
pace and drivers turned on their fog lights, while police patrol
cars cruised the streets. One policemen on duty on the Second Ring
Road in the city's central part said they were holding the speed
of cars around there to 30 kilometers per hour in a bid to reduce
the chance of traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
The Municipal Traffic Control Bureau officials were out on
major streets early this morning to help keep traffic order.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fog has brought inconveniences to local residents. Many
bus commuters were late for work today. One young man hurrying by
on his bike was out of breath and said he found it hard to breathe
on his way to work.
</P>
<P>
According to the Beijing Meteorology Administration, all of
northern China was shrouded in heavy morning fog, and visibility
at the Meteorological Observatory at eight o'clock this morning
was merely 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
Around 8 AM Wednesday, heavy fog caused two traffic accidents
on the Beijing-Tianjin Expressway with a chain of reactions, each
involving more than 40 vehicles, and leaving nine passengers dead
and many others injured.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Tianjin, approximately 120 km east of Beijing,
the fog was reported to have lingered on for three consecutive
days, and the port operation came to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
Some cases of carbon monoxide poisoning have been reported in
Tianjin, and the number of colds has soared to a new high because
of pollution levels in the city. Weather forecasters were advising
people to stay home if at all possible.
</P>
<P>
Back in Beijing, the fog was lifting by noon today, and the
first flight, headed for Kuwait, left the airport at 11:45 AM. And
seven flights left within 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
However, meteorologists noted that the fog will become even
heavier this afternoon, but northern China is expected to be
assaulted by a cold front on Friday morning, which will help
disperse the fog in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
