<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North City Embraced by Warm Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Harbin, capital city of China's
northernmost province of Heilongjiang, is witnessing the third
warmest winter since 1949.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial meteorological station, the
temperature for November averaged -2.5 degrees centigrade, 3.2
degrees higher than that of an average year and the third highest
one for November in the city since 1949.
</P>
<P>
The previous highs were -2.1 degrees centigrade for November of
1990, and -2.4 degrees centigrade for those of 1975 and 1994, said
Cai Yunqi, a senior meteorologist with the station.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of December, the average temperature
remained nearly two degrees higher than that of an average year,
and the higher temperature is expected to last throughout the
month.
</P>
<P>
Cai explained that the direct cause for the warm winter is that
cold eddies from the north pole, having stayed in the region above
60 degrees north latitude, has not exerted its influence on Harbin.
</P>
<P>
Reputed to be the coldest provincial capital in China, Harbin
has its biggest winter attraction in the annual ice and snow
festival. Due to the warm winter, the four snowfalls so far this
year has left few traces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
