<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Economic Growth Slowed Down in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in Africa in
1997 slowed down to three percent from 4.4 percent in 1996,
today's Zambia Daily Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a United Nation's report published Monday as
saying that economic weakening in Morocco and South Africa as
well as in Kenya, Malawi, Tanzania, Tunisia, Zambia and Zimbabwe
also contributed to the slowdown.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "The World Economy at the Beginning of
1998", said the economic expansion is nevertheless widespread and
relatively strong in over one-third of the countries monitored.
</P>
<P>
The two most significant factors behind the surge in growth
that Africa enjoyed in 1996, namely, high oil prices and improved
agricultural output, contributed much less to growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report said oil prices declined and agricultural
production fell in many countries, including in Ethiopia, South
Africa and Zambia, after bumper crops raised agricultural output
to record levels in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Growth in Africa, said the report, is forecast to rebound to
about four percent in 1998, as the weather-related factors that
slowed growth in 1997 are expected to be temporary in most
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the El Nino weather phenomenon raises the likelihood
of poor rains for the 1997-1998 crop season, particularly in
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Africa's economic growth could also be adversely affected in
1998 if export growth is held back by the currency crisis and
economic slowdown in east Asian countries, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Projects Backed by Thai Investment Board Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The value of projects promoted
by the government's Board of Investment (BOI) is likely to drop by
almost 19 percent in terms of the baht this year, according to BOI
Secretary-General Staporn Kavitanon.
</P>
<P>
The total value of BOI-supported investment projects for this
year is likely to be only 430 billion baht (9.42 U.S. dollars
calculated at the present exchange rate), compared with 529.4
billion baht (20.76 billion dollars calculated at the exchange
rate of last year) last year.
</P>
<P>
The decline reflects the overall slowdown in the domestic
economy and the investment climate is expected to be even weaker,
Staporn said on Wednesday at a BOI meeting chaired by Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai, who is also the BOI chairman.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, applications for promotional privileges have
come from 970 projects worth a total of 500 million baht, while
last year applications came from 1,197 projects worth 834.6
billion baht (32.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
A report at the meeting said that 24 large projects worth 116
billion baht, granted BOI privileges between 1993 and 1997, had
canceled their plans, and another 40 large projects have been
temporarily suspended.
</P>
<P>
However, Staporn said he is optimistic that the depreciation of
the baht would help boost growth in some investment sectors,
especially export-oriented and supporting industries such as
electronics, auto parts and agribusiness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
