<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR Detains Two Bosnian Croats Indicted for War Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 18 (Xinhua) -- NATO chief Javier Solana
Thursday announced that the NATO-led multinational Stabilization
Force (SFOR) had detained two Bosnian Croats indicted for war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's secretary general said that the capture of
Vlatko Kupreskic and Anto Furundzija was made during the night of
Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The duo were indicted by the International Criminal Tribunal
for former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that the action was taken in accordance with SFOR's
mandate which authorizes it to detain such persons when
encountered in the course of its duties.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR mandate, the NATO chief added, was given by the North
Atlantic Council, NATO's executive agency, under authority
contained in the relevant United Nations Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"As has been the case throughout the IFOR and SFOR missions, we
will not tolerate any behavior by any party contrary to the
(Dayton) peace agreement," said Solana. "As confirmed this week by
NATO foreign ministers, SFOR will continue its firm and
even-handed approach to implementing its mandate and supporting
civil implementation."
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers endorsed during their Tuesday's meeting
the conclusions of NATO defense ministers of keeping SFOR at its
current force levels in Bosnia until next June to further
implement the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers argued that peace and the civil
implementation to uphold it are still fragile in
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Solana said, "This action by SFOR stands as a warning to all
those indicted for war crimes who are still at large that they,
too, will be held accountable."
</P>
<P>
"They should take steps immediately to surrender themselves
voluntarily to the International Criminal Tribunal for former
Yugoslavia," Solana added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
