<HEADLINE> National Housing Bank Proposed in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
been urged to set up a national housing bank to put together
financial resources to facilitate housing provision, according to
weekly Financial Mail.
</P>
<P>
Zambia University, the highest learning institute in the
country, proposed that the funds from government, the community,
the private sector and the international community be put
together in one basket and then be channeled to the construction
industry at affordable interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The university said in a study that houses, especially for the
low-income and medium income groups, should be constructed either
partially or completely externally while the occupants can
complete the houses after occupying them, thus making houses more
affordable.
</P>
<P>
The local weekly quoted it as further recommending that
concessions and fiscal incentives such as the reduction of duties
on equipment, machinery and capital goods required by the
construction will do a lot of good to the provision of housing
stocks.
</P>
<P>
These concession should also be given to companies which
assist their employees in acquiring their own houses, said the
study.
</P>
<P>
During the survey by the university, most respondents said
that the government should give loans to those wanting to build
houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
