<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Province Promotes Shareholding System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Heilongjiang, China's
northernmost province and a leading industrial center, is actively
deepening the reform of state and collective enterprises by
introducing shareholding enterprises and cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
According to a provincial official, the province has already
established over 8,000 shareholding enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, compared with the developed areas in China,
shareholding enterprises in Heilongjiang are small in both number
and scale, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to deepen the reform, the province has called
for all enterprises with a sharp competitive edge to gradually
become sole proprietorships or shareholding companies in which the
state equity share exceeds 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
This will include industries producing special goods or
enjoying special state support.
</P>
<P>
The province has also called for well-equipped debt-ridden
enterprises to resort to diversified methods of reform, including
transforming debt into shares and turning revenue or unpaid taxes
into state-owned share capital.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises and institutions are encouraged to purchase shares in
the new enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Shareholding cooperatives have been suggested for numerous
small to medium-sized state and collective firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urged to Combat Transnational Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has called on
law enforcers of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) to come up with a concerted plan of action to address
transnational crimes in the region.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Interior and Local Government Secretary Robert
Barbers made the call here Thursday when he inaugurated the
Experts Meeting of the First ASEAN Conference on Transnational
Crimes.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-seven participants representing police, prosecution and
interior offices from the nine ASEAN countries are taking part in
the three-day conference.
</P>
<P>
"I challenge all of you attending this meeting to draw up a
concerted plan of action to address this problem," Barbers said.
</P>
<P>
Barbers called on the delegates to practice the ASEAN spirit of
unity, cooperation and solidarity in the fight against
transnational crimes, especially the newer forms -- phantom ship
frauds, product counterfeiting, piracy and fraudulent travel
documents.
</P>
<P>
Barbers said that the nature of transnational crime today has
become more complicated, prevalent and destructive, that the time
has come for an integrated ASEAN effort to effectively combat
these criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
The Experts Meeting will last until Saturday when the Ministers
Meeting will take place.
</P>
<P>
The ministers from the nine ASEAN countries are expected to
sign an ASEAN declaration against transnational crimes, a document
which will serve to hasten the formation of an integrated body
which will deal with transnational crimes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
