<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier On Hong Kong, Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen has said China is confident
about Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and stability, despite the
impact of the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a recent interview with People's Daily,
China's leading newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Administration by the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) has remained in good order over the
past five-odd months since China resumed the exercise of
sovereignty in Hong Kong on July 1 this year, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The principles of "one country, two systems", "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" and "a high-degree of autonomy" have been
implemented in a substantive and effective manner, he added.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR has maintained prosperity and stability, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis which has affected Southeast Asia
has imposed some danger on the HKSAR, with the region's stock
exchange fluctuating by a wide margin and the Hong Kong dollar
unable to avoid related influences, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that measures adopted by the HKSAR
government, as well as the region's huge volume of foreign
exchange reserves, mature financial supervision and sound
financial policies have enabled Hong Kong to be in good
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China is fully confident about Hong Kong's future,
and noted that the central government and all the Chinese people
will offer powerful backing for the HKSAR and Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Hong Kong will continue to be a free harbor
and a center for international finance, trade and transportation,
and will maintain long-term prosperity and stability", said Qian.
</P>
<P>
On Taiwan's "practical diplomacy", Qian said that
reunification of the motherland is the common aspiration of
the Chinese people throughout the world, and that relations across
Taiwan Straits have gained greater attention since Hong Kong's
return.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Qian, the trend for splittism which has
developed inside Taiwan has severely hindered the progress of a
peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the Taiwan authorities, faced
with pressure from various circles, has adopted a pose of
willingness to negotiate with the mainland. On the other hand,
however, they adhere to a position of splittism and make the
recognition of Taiwan as an "independent and sovereign state" a
precondition for negotiations. "This is completely counter
to the aspirations and demands of the Chinese people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian cited President Jiang Zemin's words in his report to the
15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party that as the
first step the two sides should conduct negotiations and reach an
agreement on formally ending hostilities in line with the "one
China" principle and then they should shoulder common obligations
to safeguard China's sovereignty and territorial integrity, and
draft plans for the future development of the relations across the
Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope that the Taiwan authorities will follow the
historical development trend and seize the opportunity to make an
active reaction and wise choice regarding political negotiations
between the two sides", said Qian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
