<HEADLINE> African Media Conference Held in Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 40 African
journalists from 16 countries have converged in Kampala to
discuss their role in the conflicts in the continent and
development of their countries, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Ruhakana Rugunda, Ugandan Information Minister, advised the
journalists to report the development in the continent correctly
and accurately.
</P>
<P>
Products of journalists will influence the decision-makers, he
noted in his opening address Monday.
</P>
<P>
African journalists must be aware that they are working under
the circumstances that Africans are made to perceive reality in
western terms, so African must be liberated in their mind first,
the minister reminded the participants of the conference.
</P>
<P>
He urged the participants not only to assist in the resolution
of conflicts and the promotion of peace but also to identify the
fundamental causes of such conflicts with a view to preventing
them.
</P>
<P>
African journalists responded to the minister warmly.
Uncorrect reports are retarding development and deepening anarchy
in the continent, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Adbulraheem Tajudeen, the Secretary General of the Pan-African
Movement, said African media should be sources of information to
local people but not to be perpetrating unconfirmed sources from
imperialists.
</P>
<P>
The conference, organized by the Center for Conflict
Resolution, will end its deliberations today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
