<HEADLINE> Australia And Fiji Join To Fight Child Sex Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian and Fiji
governments will work together to stamp out child sex abuse in the
Pacific area following ministerial talks between the two countries
held Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Alexander Downer said, there had been
allegations of Australians committing child sex abuse in Fiji and
he hoped the joint action would discourage Australians from
looking to Pacific island countries as a paedophile destination.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's incumbent on the Australian government to do
everything it can to stamp that out," Downer was quoted by
Australian Associated Press from Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
"The way to do that is to enhance substantially the cooperation
between the various law enforcement agencies exchanging
information with each other, working together in a number of
different ways.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's going to make a big difference that we'll work
together much more closely in this area than was the case in the
past."
</P>
<P>
According to Downer, the discussions provided a framework to
strengthen cooperation on child sex abuse and other serious
crimes, but final details of an agreement would have to be
approved by the Fiji Cabinet later.
</P>
<P>
At today's talks, Downer and his counterpart Fiji Foreign
Affairs Minister Berenado Vunibobo also discussed an agreement to
negotiate advances in trade and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Downer said he wanted to encourage Australians to invest in
Fiji which had fixed up constitutional problems, making the
country more attractive to investors, and cited tourism as a key
growth area.
</P>
<P>
"Australia's trade with Fiji is in the vicinity of a billion
dollars so it's quite a substantial trade. Nevertheless, we want
to continue to develop that trade and where there are obstacles,
particularly administrative obstacles to that trade, we want to
try to remove or diminish those obstacles," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade and economic agreement is expected to be
finalized by June 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
