<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Land Reform Not to Drive Whites Out: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 4,000 white
commercial farmers have been invited to come forward and work out
modalities on how the land redistribution program could be
speeded up for the benefit of all interested parties in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"The Herald" today quoted Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
as saying in an interview with Cable News Network (CNN) Wednesday
that the land redistribution program was not meant to drive the
white commercial farmers out of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The government wanted to fairly distribute the land to
landless Zimbabweans who did not have enough land to fend for
themselves," he added.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Zimbabwean government has decided to acquire
about 1,500 farms or five million hectares for resettlement and
commercial farming for the landless indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told CNN it was unfortunate that only about 4,000
farmers in the country owned about three-quarters of the best
land at the expense of the majority of Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was determined to carry the land
apportionment program forward despite reservations expressed by
Britain over compensating the farmers for the lost land.
</P>
<P>
He dispelled rumors that the government ministers owned most
of the under-used farms that were not designated. This was
"nonsense" since only a few of the 22 cabinet members owned
farms.
</P>
<P>
He assured the nation that the landless people of Zimbabwe
would definitely get a piece of land as the government wanted to
answer the people's grievances on land and ensure that peace and
stability prevailed in the country.
</P>
<P>
Responding to whether the white community still have a place
in the country or not, Mugabe said, "surely, yes. There is a lot
of land in Zimbabwe. They still have a place to live."
</P>
<P>
He further stressed that the land apportionment exercise was
not meant to drive them out but to create an atmosphere which was
conducive to the majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
