<HEADLINE> Gas Negotiations Between Bulgaria, Russia in Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Russian-Bulgarian
negotiations over Russia's supply of natural gas to Bulgaria have
been stranded as a result of the indefinite suspension of a joint
stock company operated by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The suspension was announced during a meeting of the
shareholders of the Topenergy Joint Stock Company in Moscow on
Tuesday, which also discussed the possible reincorporation of the
company.
</P>
<P>
In the session, the two Bulgarian private giants Multigrup and
Overgaz failed to sell their shares to Bulgaria's Natural Gas
Company (NGC), the official shareholder of Topenergy as required
in a contact signed by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The NGC, in return, announced on the same day, its retreat from
Topenergy. As a direct consequence, the Russian-Bulgarian
negotiations over the contracts on Russia's supply of natural gas
to Bulgaria have to be postponed until next year.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian government decided this July to have the NGC buy
8.25 percent of shares of Multigrup and Overgaz in a bid to help
the NGC own an equal share in its business with its Russian
counterpart by holding 50 percent of Topenergy shares.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the Russian natural gas company to
Topenergy refused Tuesday to meet with related Bulgarian energy
officials on the issue after Topenergy's full session "failed" to
provide conditions for breaking the current deadlock of bilateral
gas supply negotiations, local media said.
</P>
<P>
Afraid of the business deadlock's possible harm to
Russian-Bulgarian relations, Bulgarian Deputy Prime Minister
Yevgeny Bakardzhiev criticized the two private companies for
breaking their promises.
</P>
<P>
Bakardzhiev said on behalf of his government, Bulgaria will
hold direct talks with the Russian government or Russia's natural
gas company, keeping clear of the "intermediary."
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian energy officials said that if Russia stops its gas
supply, Bulgaria will "look for support from the West."
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian official newspaper "Democracy" Wednesday also
criticized Multigrup and Overgaz for their business perfidy,
saying that it is "blackmail" to the country.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian state TV reports said Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan
is trying to contact his Russian counterpart Viktor Chernomyrdin
on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
