<HEADLINE> 27,000 Observers to Monitor Kenya's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- An expected 27,635 observers
representing 25 foreign and eight local organizations will
monitor the December 29 elections across Kenya, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Most of them will represent the National Council of Churches
of Kenya (NCCK), the Catholic Justice and Peace Commission and
the Institute for Education in Democracy (IED), said the reports.
</P>
<P>
These groups will work as a team and send two observers per
polling station -- one inside and the other outside, said
Electoral Commission Chairman Samuel Kivuitu on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the embassies to observe the poll are those of Poland,
Germany, Netherlands, Indonesia, Greece, Belgium, Australia,
Sweden, Ethiopia, the U.S., Czech Republic, Italy, Norway, Japan,
Hungary, Britain, Austria, Denmark, France, Spain and Canada.
</P>
<P>
It was expected the observer arrangement could help maintain
peace and order on the election day.
</P>
<P>
Scores of people were injured and a number of cars stoned in
Kenya's third-largest city of Kisumu on Wednesday when supporters
of presidential candidates Daniel arap Moi, Charity Ngilu and
Raila Odinga met face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
Two Kenyans have been killed and at least 50 arrested over
election-related violence countrywide since November 15.
</P>
<P>
Nine of the total 15 presidential candidates had requested and
been given round-the-clock security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
