<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's voters go to the polls Thursday, an
official holiday, to elect a new president who will lead the
country through its current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16,407 polling stations opened at 6 a.m. and will
close at 6 p.m. for the 32.29 million eligible voters. Ballot
counting will start at about 7 p.m., and the results of the
election are expected to be released by Friday morning.
(SKorea-Presidential Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will announce
Wednesday that U.S. troops will continue to be deployed in Bosnia
when the mandate of the current Stabilization Force (SFOR) expires
next June, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on Tuesday, Clinton said he
would announce his plans before his flight to Bosnia, where he is
to visit the U.S. troops and meet Bosnian leaders. The size of the
follow-on force and its American contingent will depend on
arrangements to be worked out with NATO allies, said the
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. (US-Bosnia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian government Special Commission on Taxation
and Budget resolved Wednesday to rectify the financial system
within the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian government's press secretary Igor
Shabdurasulov, the commission, which had a meeting Wednesday
presided over by Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, decided to
rectify the methods for regulating the defense budget, and the
soldiers' pay and provisions expenses. (Russia-Defense-Financial
Regulation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said on Wednesday
that Thailand's economy would start to recover after four to five
months.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on revision of the Eight National Development Plan
(1995-1999), he indicated that the worst times for the economy are
anticipated in the next four to five months, adding that matters
would remain critical for five to six months, particularly if the
country fell short of revenue targets. The situation has changed
dramatically since the Eighth National Development Plan was made
and now it is a good opportunity to review strategy and the
direction of development and adopt appropriate guidelines for the
rest of the plan period, he added. (Thailand-Economy-PM) 
</P>
</TEXT>
