<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister on International Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen recently noted that the overall trend
of the current international situation is gaining speed towards
multi-polarization.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with People's Daily, Qian pointed to many
changes in the international situation and relations between major
powers during 1997.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the demand for independence, self-reliance and
coordinated development is on the rise both on a regional basis
and in the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Relations between major powers have been reshaped from a
strategic perspective, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that various regional and multilateral cooperative
mechanisms are expanding, and developing countries are becoming an
undeniable force in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that economic elements have become
increasingly prominent in international relations and countries
are becoming more interdependent.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Southeast Asia has affected many
nations and areas, and the governments of all countries are faced
with the task of strengthening coordination in the process of
economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that partnerships established between major powers
signal the fact that such relations are gaining greater stability
than even before.
</P>
<P>
Qian said frequent contacts between the United States, European
nations and Russia on European affairs, and bilateral meetings
between leaders of China, the United States, Japan and Russia have
attracted worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
He said readjustments in relations between different countries
will help to build an international environment conducive to the
development of their respective countries and are their strategic
choice geared to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed out that a common characteristic of the various
partnerships is to seek the convergence of their common
interests. He noted that the readjustments in relations conform
with the historical trend of peace and development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
