<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Home Affairs Minister Declines to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Minister of Home
Affairs Dumiso Dabengwa has said he will not resign from cabinet
unless the people, and not the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions
(ZCTU), want him to, "The Herald" daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Responding to calls by ZCTU President Gibson Sibanda for him
and Police Commissioner Augustine Chihuri to resign, Dabengwa
told the herald Wednesday that he would resign any day if the
people supported Sibanda's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
Sibanda Tuesday demanded the immediate resignation of Dabengwa
and Chihuri, warning that another mass demonstration would be
organized to back this demand.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU accuses the two men of hampering last week's
demonstrations in Harare and of being behind the assault of ZCTU
Secretary-general Morgan Tsvangirai by about eight unidentified
assailants last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, "it looks like the ZCTU wants the
government to collapse so they can take over as has happened
elsewhere on this continent because they have no basis for even
threatening another mass demonstration."
</P>
<P>
He said the demonstration in Harare was only dispersed because
some hooligans had started looting shops as early as 7 a.m. The
police had the support of the people to stop the demonstration,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
