<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Test and Appraise Police Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Some one million Chinese
policemen will be tested and undergo appraisals of their
professional and physical capabilities over the next two years,
according to a notice recently issued by the Ministry of Public
Security.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the notice, which will be implemented in 36
major cities, is to improve the basic quality of the national
police force, according to a ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Chinese police authorities have pledged to offer periodical
organized in-service training courses to help all police officers
pass the test and appraisals in order to form a truly professional
force.
</P>
<P>
"Those who fail the test or the appraisal will be
temporarily relieved and will undergo a six month training
course," according to the notice. "Those who fail after taking
training courses will be dismissed from their posts."
</P>
<P>
The ministry also has plans to test and appraise directors of
public security bureaus at county level, "with the dismissal of
officials unqualified for their positions," according to the
notice.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Public Security pointed out
that the fundamental means for improving the basic quality of the
national police force centers on encouraging competition and
supervision, and on implementing a regular testing and appraisal
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
