<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Cooperation in Southern Africa Enters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa, a
region which has suffered from frequent civil wars, reportedly has
some 20 million mines scattered and that has become a great
impediment to post-war reconstruction in countries like Mozambique
and Angola.
</P>
<P>
To solve this critical problem, SADC leaders to the Blantyre
summit signed a landmark declaration, calling for Southern Africa
free of anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this, South Africa, a political, economical and
military power in Africa, took the lead in announcing in February
to impose a comprehensive and immediate ban on anti-personnel
landmines.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria's attitude towards mines prompted representatives of
SADC countries to meet in Harare, Zimbabwe, in April to discuss
regional and international cooperation in mine clearance on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
"The gathering marked a turning point in efforts to free the
Southern African region of landmines," said Cornelio Sommaruga,
President of the International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The southern African countries also tried to join hands to
curb increasing crimes in the region. On October 1, an agreement
was signed by SADC countries to promote cooperation and
integration in fight against cross-border crimes.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the signatory countries will cooperate
one another and offer all convenience in the process of
investigating suspects.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SADC posed to become important partners in the
world economy. Its cooperation with the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) in the fields of trade and investment is
one of the examples.
</P>
<P>
Following inaugural talks between ASEAN and SADC ministers at
last year's meeting of the World Trade Organization in Singapore,
a second meeting was held in Kuala Lumpur in mid-October this
year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from steps to promote trade and investment between the
two regions, the meeting also discussed cooperation in technical
assistance, education and human resouces development.
</P>
<P>
Currently, South Africa has become a major recipient of direct
investment from Malaysia, which has poured an estimated three
U.S. billion dollars into the country, making it the second
largest foreign investor for South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The SADC's trade with Middle East countries, especially Iran,
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates has also been
on increase in the past few year.
</P>
<P>
The SADC is also looking forward to enhancing its
economic and trading ties with the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) in Latin America, which groups Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay, with Chile and Bolivia being associate
members.
</P>
<P>
While the SADC is making headway in the political and economic
fields, one must realize the regional group is also facing some
thorny problems.
</P>
<P>
One of the most critical problems facing it is trade
imbalance. Some countries such as South Africa, Zimbabwe and
Mauritius are accused of being protectionists, trying to dominate
the region by placing high tariffs on imports, thus making
exports from other SADC members uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
What is more, social problems like poverty, unemployment,
crime and political democracy remained to be solved in many
Southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that economic backwardness and
poverty are the hotbed of all unstable elements. In this sense,
SADC member states can never succeed unless each of them spares
no efforts to develop its own economy while maintaining close
ties with other nations in the SADC framework.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the economic development disparity among member
states and disputes on trade and economic integration, analysts
said that the SADC, as a rising regional leader, will ultimately
overcome problems facing it and lead the nations into political
stability and economic prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
