<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Three Major Issues Related to Return of Macao to Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The three major issues related
to the return of Macao to the motherland, namely the localization
of civil servants and laws and the status of Chinese as an
official language, have become more urgent for solution as the
return of Macao approaches.
</P>
<P>
Observers here say that these issues are important for the
implementation of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration and the
principles of "one country, two systems", "Macao people governing
Macao" and "high-degree of autonomy" set forth in the Basic Law
of the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
The issues are also closely related to the practical interests
of the people of Macao and a smooth transition, they say.
</P>
<P>
There has been some progress in solving the three issues in
recent years, thanks to the efforts made by China and Portugal,
but it is still not enough.
</P>
<P>
Because there are only two years left until Macao returns
to the motherland, there is still much work to do, the media
report.
</P>
<P>
The localization of civil servants is regarded the most urgent
of the three issues, observers say. According to the Basic Law of
the Macao SAR, major officials of Macao should be Chinese citizens
who are permanent residents of the region.
</P>
<P>
They say that it is only when more Chinese residents of Macao
serve as senior civil servants can the principle of "Macao
people governing Macao" be realized after Macao returns to the
motherland on December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
China and Portugal have agreed to accomplish the localization
of civil servants above the director level by the end of 1998, and
the Chinese government hopes that the Portuguese side will
accelerate the process.
</P>
<P>
At present, directors and vice-directors of Chinese origin in
the Macao government account for only 13.5 percent of the total,
and the first director of Chinese origin took office only in
November this year.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese is still the most frequently used language in
government operations, although Chinese is being used in many
government departments. Documents issued by some government
departments are only in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
In the localization of laws, only two of the five local codes
-- the criminal code and criminal procedure code -- have so far
been adapted to Macao.
</P>
<P>
The localization of the three others -- the civil code, the
civil procedure code and the commercial code -- should also be
accelerated, and Macao should train a judiciary to serve the
future SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
