<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on China's Relations with Other Powers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- China has moved forward in its
relations with the United States, Russia, Japan and the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen made the
statement in a recent interview with People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
He said the positive development in Sino-US relations this year
was marked by Chinese President Jiang Zemin's successful state
visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the leaders of the two countries reached an important
agreement on the framework and development direction for bilateral
relations geared to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed the two countries should approach their
relationship from a long-term perspective and on the basis of the
three Sino-US joint communiques, said Qian, adding that they
decided to build a constructive strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
He noted that bilateral relations will develop in a healthy and
stable way as long as the two sides strictly abide by the
principles embodied in the three Sino-US joint communiques in
dealing with Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that China and Russia have established a strategic and
cooperative partnership of equality and mutual trust for the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang visited Russia in April 1997. He and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin signed a joint statement on global
multi-polarization and the establishment of a new international
order, according to Qian.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Yeltsin visited China in November 1997,
with the two heads of state holding their fifth summit and
reaching an agreement on settling demarcation of the eastern
section of the Sino-Russian border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on China's Relations with Other Powers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qian said that the prime ministers of China and Japan exchanged
visits this year, and agreed to develop good-neighborly relations
of cooperation oriented toward the 21st century on the basis of
the Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of
Peace and Friendship.
</P>
<P>
He noted that President Jiang's visit to Japan next year will
further promote the soundness of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that relations between China and members of the EU have
developed steadily this year.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed to French President Jacques Chirac's visit to
China in May 1997, and noted that the two countries decided to
build a comprehensive partnership geared to the 21st century and
called for multi-polarization.
</P>
<P>
He said that Sino-German relations have developed continuously,
along with expanded bilateral cooperation. He also noted that
China and Britain worked together to realize the smooth transfer
of power in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China believes that more dialog and cooperation
between China and Europe are in the realistic and long-term
interests of the two sides, and will be conducive to world peace,
stability and prosperity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
