<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Downturn Lowers Australian Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian Treasurer Peter
Costello Thursday conceded the expected downturn in Asia had
lowered Australia's short-term prospects for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the federal government's mid-year economic and fiscal
outlook, Costello said he expected the effect of the financial
instability in Asia would be felt more in next 1998-99 financial
year.
</P>
<P>
"Financial instability in several Asian economies has lowered
short-term growth prospects for the region," Costello said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"The effect in Australia is likely to be felt more in 1998-99
than in 1997-98."
</P>
<P>
Costello said the preliminary forecasts for 1998-99 indicate
that economic growth is expected to be about 3.25 percent, "weaker
than the anticipated outcome for 1997-98".
</P>
<P>
"Australia's strong and improving fiscal position has been
important in helping to shield the economy from the instability
experienced in some other countries in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The mid-year review maintained the growth forecast for 1997-98
of 3.75 percent, with stronger domestic demand offsetting the
weaker external picture caused by the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
But the slower growth resulting from a weaker international
environment was expected to impact on employment growth, though
not until later in the financial year.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, employment growth through 1998-99 is likely to be
similar to that through 1997-98," the outlook said.
</P>
<P>
On the budget position, the review showed the underlying
deficit for 1997-98 narrowed to 2.8 billion Australian dollars
(1.87 billion U.S. dollars) from the preliminary forecast of 3.9
billion Australian dollars (2.61 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Due to the greater-than-expected proceeds of asset sales,
including the one-third privatization of Telstra
(Telecommunication Company), the headline surplus almost doubled
to 11.782 billion Australian dollars (7.89 Billion U.S. dollars)
from 6.4 billion Australian dollars (4.28 billion U.S. dollars) on
budget night.  
</P>
</TEXT>
