<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Cooperation in Southern Africa Enters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries
which witnessed encouraging achievements in regional cooperation
in the past few years have come to realize that economic development
and political stability are of most importance in promoting cooperation
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Africa has been frequented by conflicts, coups and waves of
refugee for decades, but positive changes have taken place in the
passing year in this part of the world, especially in southern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to an official survey, gross domestic product in
Southern Africa has increased by more than six percent since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in southern Africa covered the fields of energy,
transport and communication, culture and information, agriculture,
fisheries and human resources development.
</P>
<P>
Three development corridors -- Maputo, Beira, and Nacala
jointly undertaken by South Africa, Zimbabwe and Mozambique are
widely regarded as good examples of regional cooperations, which
will greatly benefit the national economic development of the
three countries.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) stands out
as a strong flagship in regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The SADC, born in 1992 with 10 member states at the beginning,
has been devoting itself to the establishment of a free trade
zone in Southern Africa by 2004, and has become one of the most
effective and efficient regional groups in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Although the magnificent plan of the SADC is yet to be
realized, more and more African countries have come to realize
that the SADC will be a strong force in promoting economic
integration, cooperation and regional stability.
</P>
<P>
At its 17th annual summit, held in Blantyre, Malawi, on
September 8, the SADC accepted two new members -- the Democratic
Republic of Congo, formerly known as Zaire, and the Seychelles,
making the 12 member grouping 14. They are Angola, Botswana, Lesotho,
Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe and the two new comers.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the organization shows its growing attraction
and influence in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, two important protocols on trade and mining
were signed. Economically speaking, the summit has paved way for
further economic cooperation since the mining industry is an
important employment channel and a major foreign exchange
earner for many member states.
</P>
<P>
While attaching great importance to economic development,
the SADC also took an active part in political affairs in the
region and the continent as a whole. ( to be continued )


=12180626

=12180635
NNNN
14:24 14:25 g # PAB
</P>
