<HEADLINE> NZ to Remove Car Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Government
announced today it will scrap the tariff on imported cars from
December 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister John Luxton said removing the tariff would
lead to cheaper cars and light commercial vehicles for families
and businesses, and removing it was an essential element in the
Government's strategy for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He said the tariff would be reduced by 2.5 percent a year from
the current 22.5 percent to 15 percent on July 1, 2000, and would
go altogether at the end of that year.
</P>
<P>
"Tariffs not only increase the price of new cars by around
3,000 NZ dollars to 4,000 NZ dollars (1,750 to 2,300 US dollars)
but are also a significant component in the price of a used
vehicle," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The move will cost the Government 300 million dollars (1.75
million US dollars) a year in tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Economists, car dealers and unions are all predicting that the
move will kill the local car assembly industry, which employs
1,500 workers and hundreds of others in related industries. Even
Luxton acknowledged on Thursday the local motor industry was
likely to close.  
</P>
</TEXT>
