<HEADLINE> KLM, Alitalia Form Strategic Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Italian carrier Alitalia
announced today it has formed an alliance with Dutch airline KLM
and will consider a possible merger after a period of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint communique issued today, the two sides
will rearrange the routes and booking systems, making Amsterdam,
Milan, Malpensa and the Rome airport the bases of their
cooperation. The alliance, however, involves no exchange of stock
and no immediate merger is planned.
</P>
<P>
Alitalia made the choice in its effort to enhance profits and
sharpen its competitive edge before moving toward privatization
next year.
</P>
<P>
The choice of KLM instead of Air France had been expected,
despite reports that the Italian government was keen to
consolidate an industrial axis with Paris.
</P>
<P>
The French government had also pressed diplomatically for the
alliance with Alitalia, but the airlines managing director,
Domenico Cempella, was known to favor the Dutch option because it
would guarantee Alitalia's independence and further privatization.
</P>
<P>
The press here published figures showing that the KLM, with 27
fewer planes and transporting just over half of Alitalia's
passengers, managed to fly to more places and turned a healthy
profit.
</P>
<P>
The KLM had net profits of 205 billion Lire (119 million
U.S. dollars) in the year to March 1997, while Alitalia recorded
losses of 1.2 trillion Lire (579 million U.S. dollars) during 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch flag-carrier, KLM, the 10th largest airline in the
world, was privatized in 1986. At present only 25 percent of its
stock is in the hands of public authorities, while the remainder
is quoted on stock markets in Amsterdam, New York, Brussels and
Frankfurt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
