<HEADLINE> 5,300-Year-Old Mummy to Be Returned to Italy for Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The 5,300-year-old remains of a
prehistoric man, found on the Italian-Austrian border, will be
returned from Austria to Italy for permanent exhibition by January
20, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In Bolzano, a museum with a refrigerated cell has been set up
to house the mummy. Objects found beside the body, including
leather clothes and shoes, an axe, a quiver for arrows and a
flint, will also be on display in March next year.
</P>
<P>
The mummy was found on September 19, 1991 by an Austrian
couple, who, during a mountain excursion, accidentally stumbled on
the frozen body at an altitude of 3,200 meters in the Similaun
Glacier in Italy's Alto Adige region.
</P>
<P>
Scientists had to be called in, however, to determine on which
side of the Italian-Austrian border the body was found, as the two
countries both claimed ownership of the mummy.
</P>
<P>
Italy won the dispute. The Austrians, who had whisked the
mummy off for studies at the Prehistory Institute of the
University of Innsbruck, finally agreed to return the mummy later.
</P>
<P>
Studies have shown the man, which the Italians called the
Similaun Man, was 45 years old when he died of cold and
suffocation about 5,300 years ago. It was the oldest human
remains found in Europe until the fall of 1996, when the bodies of
two children living some 6,500 years ago were discovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
