<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Lower House Passes Bankruptcy Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The House of Representatives
of Thailand has passed a relaxed bankruptcy bill to allow debtors
and creditors more flexibility in negotiating their debt payment
and reorganizing businesses instead of immediate closure.
</P>
<P>
The house on Wednesday approved in its third reading the bill
proposed by the Chavalit Yongchaiyudh government in August this
year to amend the present one to reflect the existing economic
troubles in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Under the new bill, debtors and creditors are allowed to find
alternatives to settle debt problems instead of filing suit in
court and liquidating assets, which can cause substantial losses
to both sides.
</P>
<P>
The new bill sets a more strict timetable for bankruptcy cases
and it requires a company to submit a rehabilitation plan to the
court within three months after the bankruptcy case is filed, with
only two revisions allowed before the court approves the plan
within five months.
</P>
<P>
The court also can appoint an independent agent or creditor to
oversee business rehabilitation process which is allowed for five
years.
</P>
<P>
If the rehabilitation plan fails after five years, the assets
of the company will be liquidated.
</P>
<P>
The local media said that the bill will be sent to the Upper
House for review and approval and then it will become a law after
it is published in a royal gazette.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
