<HEADLINE> Russia To Rectify Defense Ministry Finances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government Special
Commission on Taxation and Budget resolved Wednesday to rectify
the financial system within the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian government's press secretary Igor
Shabdurasulov, the commission had a meeting Wednesday presided
over by Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. The commission decided
to rectify the methods for regulating the defense budget, and the
soldiers' pay and provisions expenses.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin described the financial regulation of the army as
"very bad." He said strict measures should be taken to prevent
behavior leading to the misappropriation of funds, including
personnel management measures.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin pointed out that his remarks were not directed
against the Minister of Defense Igor Sergeyev because he has held
the post for only a short time.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev told the press that the commission's decision includes
improving the financial system of the more powerful departments,
to manage the financial affairs of these departments through state
financial institutions and to enhance mutual supervision among
these departments.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said the military supervision institute has been
authorized to rectify the financial work of the army, and the
Ministry of Finance will be responsible for the reform of the
army's financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev stressed that squandering money, embezzlement and
misappropriation of public funds are all destructive to the combat
effectiveness of the army.
</P>
<P>
Reports say pecuniary losses occurring as the result of illegal
and criminal cases in the army in 1996 amounted to 100 billion
rubles (approximately 18 million US dollars). In 1997 the amount
of money squandered and embezzled in the army rose 26.8 percent,
while the amount misappropriated was up 48.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
