<HEADLINE> Clinton to Announce U.S. Keeps Troops in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will announce Wednesday that U.S. troops will continue to be
deployed in Bosnia when the mandate of the current Stabilization
Force (SFOR) expires next June, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The size of the follow-on force and its American contingent
will depend on arrangements to be worked out with NATO allies,
said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on Tuesday, Clinton said he
would announce his plans before his flight to Bosnia, where he is
to visit the U.S. troops and meet Bosnian leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is caught between pressure from
Congress asking for a complete pullout of all the 8,000 U.S.
troops and its allies who insist that peace will collapse if the
peacekeepers withdraw.
</P>
<P>
Britain, France and other European countries have indicated
that they would withdraw their troops from Bosnia if the U.S.
does.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the administration's lack of an exit strategy on
the peacekeeping mission, many lawmakers in the U.S. Congress fear
that the U.S. troops may be caught up in any flare-up of the
conflict in Bosnia if they stay longer.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has postponed two previous deadlines for the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Any further deployment of U.S. troops beyond next June will
need to be approved by the Senate and Clinton needs to explain why
it is necessary in Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
