<HEADLINE> South Korea's Voters Go to Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's voters will go to
the polls Thursday, an official holiday, to elect a new president
who will lead the country through its current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16,407 polling stations opened at 6 a.m. and will
close at 6 p.m. for the 32.29 million eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
Ballot counting will start at about 7 p.m., and the results of
the election are expected to be released by Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The three major presidential candidates -- Lee Hoi-chang of the
Grand National Party, Kim Dae-jung of the National Congress for
New Politics, and Rhee In-je voted in their respective
constituencies this morning for the single five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say Lee and Kim are running neck-and-neck, while Rhee
is trailing not far behind in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
The 62-year-old Lee, a former prime minister of the ruling
party, reportedly enjoys strong support in Taegu and the
surrounding North Kyongsang Province, while Kim, a 72-year-old
veteran opposition leader, holds an overwhelming lead in his power
base in Cholla region and Kwangju city.
</P>
<P>
The contest in Seoul is the most intense, in which voters
account for a quarter of the total.
</P>
<P>
Election officials predict that voter turnout, as a result of
the influence of the current financial crisis ailing the country,
will be lower than the previous election. And one of the
campaigners could likely become president with only 39-41 percent
of the vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
