<HEADLINE> Profile: Czech New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Josef Tosovsky was appointed as
the prime minister of the Czech Republic on Wednesday as the
second head of government after the independence of the republic
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Tosovsky, an economist and financial expert, was born on
September 28, 1950 in the city of Nachod close to the border of
Poland.
</P>
<P>
After graduation from the Department of Foreign Trade of the
Czech Economic College in 1973, Tosovsky has been enaged in
financial business.
</P>
<P>
He worked for the National Bank of the former Czechslovakia
during 1973-1984, and then the Czechslovak Commercial Bank London
Branch from 1984 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
From 1986 to 1989, Tosovsky served as a consultant to the
President of the Czechslovak National Bank and assumed the post of
the bank's president in 1992 after the division of the
Czechslovakia into two independent states in 1993. He transferred
to head the National Bank of the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
The new prime minister is not affiliated to any party. He is
married and has two daughters.
</P>
<P>
The Klaus-led former government, operative since last July, was
forced to resign on November 30.
</P>
<P>
For days, the Civic Democratic Party, Christian Democratic
Union-Czechslovak and Civic Democratic Alliance have undergone
many rounds of arduous negotiations on the formation of the new
cabinet and, particularly, the selection of a new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the appointment of Tosovsky was the result of
the combined concession made by the various parties.
</P>
<P>
They said the Tosovsky government will possibly be a
transitional one and it it likely that an early election will be
held next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
