<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Discover Herbal Treatment For Diabetes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
developed a herbal medicine which they say can be used to treat
diabetes II, which affects at least 25 million Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the China Academy of Traditional Medicines
made the medicine, "Tangmaikang", but the Ministry of Health will
not disclose the names of most of them, to protect the formula.
</P>
<P>
"'Tangmaikang' has a noticeable effect in treating
complications of diabetes by reducing cholesterol and glycerin in
the blood," Professor Fu Shiyuan, president of the academy, told a
symposium on diabetes.
</P>
<P>
Diabetes complications include heart disease, cerebral vascular
disease, kidney disease, loss of eyesight, and other serious
problems. "But, almost all the sugar-reducing drugs are no help in
treating the complications," Fu explained.
</P>
<P>
Diabetes is a metabolic disorder related to insulin, a hormone
controlling the passage of sugar from the blood to the tissue,
where excessive amounts of sugar occur in the blood and in the
urine, and are associated with loss of weight and excessive thirst.
</P>
<P>
With improved standards of living and the gradual increase in
the amount of Western-style food in the diet over the past decade,
an increasing number of people in China, India and other
developing countries are suffering from diabetes. There are at
least 750,000 new cases of diabetes in China each year, according
to a Ministry of Health official.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese researchers should do further studies on insulin
levels in patients who use Tangmaikang so that it can be accepted
by the Western medical community and be sold on the international
market," Professor Chen Keji, an advisor to the WHO and a member
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, says.
</P>
<P>
The China Academy of Traditional Chinese Medicine's Zhonghui
Pharmaceutical Co. recently built a plant to produce five billion
yuan worth of Tangmaikang annually, along with other Chinese
medicines, in Chengdu, Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
International sales of herbal medicines amount to 15 billion US
dollars annually, but Chinese traditional medicine only accounts
for 600 million US dollars of that. "The marketing of Tangmaikang
internationally will help boost exports of Chinese medicine,"
Prof. Fu comments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Sets Electronics Export Target for 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
set a target of electronic export at 35 billion U.S. dollars in
2004, the final year of the Seventh Five-Year Development Plan
(1999-2004), a government official said.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of the nation's electronics industry is mainly
the result of foreign and domestic investments, which are
continuing to pour into the industry, Director of Electronics
Industry at the Ministry of Industry and Trade Ardiansyah said
Wednesday in Bandung, West Java, reports reaching here Thursday
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on an industrial vision in the
development of national information infrastructure, Ardiansyah
said that 10 billion U.S. dollars worth of additional investments
will be needed in the next seven years to realize the target in
2004.
</P>
<P>
"If everything runs as planned, the total export value in 2006
may even reach 40 billion U.S. dollars," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the 40 billion U.S. dollars will come from the exports
of information technology equipment, wireless telecommunication
equipment, consumer electronics, semiconductors, electronic
household equipment and electronic components as well as modules.
</P>
<P>
Electronic companies in Indonesia have grown rapidly since the
beginning the 90s mainly because they are supported by
liberalization in tariffs and the reduction of bureaucratic
requirements to obtain operational licenses, he said, adding that
most of the nation's electronics companies are export oriented.
</P>
<P>
However, he acknowledged that the exported electronic goods
still contain a limited amount of local contents. The local
contents, I believe, only total around 5 percent," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
