<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income Disparities Widen in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 17 (Xinhua) -- California's poor and
middle-class families have experienced sharp income falls over the
past two decades while the richest enjoys soaring gains.
</P>
<P>
According to a new state-to-state study by the Washington-based
Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a national nonpartisan
research organization, the incomes of Californian wealthest
families which are comprised of one-fifth state population were up
30 percent since 1978, while the poorest, making up one-fifth of
the population, had lost 27 percent of the incomes they once had.
</P>
<P>
California is not the only U.S. state experiencing the widening
income disparities. In fact, the study on income trends shows that
income disparities between the richest families and families at
the bottom and middle of the income scale have grown substantially
in almost every state over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
The study also finds that despite the strong economic growth in
recent years, income disparities are significantly greater than
they were at the comparable point in the business cycle during the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
The richest families have gained their incomes by investing
their money in stock markets and financial products.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1970s, there was no state in the country where the
richest families had average incomes 10 or more times larger than
those of the poorest. But by the mid-1990s, 30 states had
"top-to-bottom" ratios of 10 or greater.
</P>
<P>
The study said that fundamental changes in the U.S. economy are
responsible for much of the growth in income disparities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Unemployment Still High: ECLAC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Urban unemployment rate
in Latin America and the Caribbean dropped slightly to 7.5 percent
in 1997 compared to 7.7 percent in 1996, but in historical terms,
it is still high, said the Economic Commission for Latin America
and the Caribbean (ECLAC) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report "Preliminary Balance of Latin America and
the Caribbean Economy - 1997," released Wednesday in Santiago, the
institution said the decline was not due to the lack of jobs but
to an increase of irregular economic activities by laid-off
workers.
</P>
<P>
Exceptions were Mexico and Argentina, where economic growth
contributed to the creation of new jobs, the report added.
</P>
<P>
However, Brazil, Colombia and Uruguay experienced a rise in the
unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
In most regions of the countries, economic reforms over recent
years that could not be assimilated led to a major loss of jobs,
explained the ECLAC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
