<HEADLINE> India Bolsters Rupee's Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) has further bolstered the defenses of the country's currency
rupee as it hovered within striking distance of all-time lows.
</P>
<P>
The RBI increased the interest charged on overdue export bills
by five percentage points to 20 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It also imposed a 15 percent surcharge on the lending rate on
import credit for select goods and commodities.
</P>
<P>
The steps taken by the RBI are aimed at persuading exporters to
bring home earnings faster and making non-essential imports
dearer, a government official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government's latest moves came after the rupee closed at
39.36/39 per U.S. dollar, much lower than before. The dealers said
the RBI spent up to 200 million dollars intervening on Tuesday to
pull the rupee away from an imminent strike at the 40 rupee per
U.S. dollar level.  
</P>
