<HEADLINE> IDB to Inject 100 Million Dollars into Indonesia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Development Bank
(IDB), together with other Islamic banks from the Middle East and
Malaysia, are planning to inject 100 million U.S. dollars into
Indonesia's capital market, IDB portfolio director B.M. Qureshy
said.
</P>
<P>
Qureshy, who led a group of commercial bankers from Kuwait,
Qatar, Bahrain and Malaysia on a visit here, said Wednesday after
meeting with Indonesian Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad that he
believed that Indonesia's economic fundamentals remained strong.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, it was agreed that IDB and some Islamic
commercial banks would help Indonesia get out of the current
monetary crisis by investing in Indonesian stocks, Thursday's
local press quoted officials at the Finance Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian stock market has nosedived alongside a sharp
fall in the value of the rupiah (national currency) since July
this year. The main market barometer closed trading Wednesday at
368.685 points compared to above 720 levels before July.
</P>
<P>
Minister Mar'ie said after the meeting that the capital
injection into Indonesian companies through the capital market was
part of the government's efforts to prop up the ailing stock
market amid the currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The value of the rupiah has dropped by more than 100 percent
following the monetary crisis in the Southeast Asian region since
July. The exchange rate of rupiah in early July was 2,360 per
dollar and it fell to 5,600 per dollar on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is the world's most populous Islamic nation. About 90
percent of its 200 million people are Muslims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
