<HEADLINE> Shanghai Putting Price Inspectors In Public Eye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The price control authorities
of Shanghai, which set price guidelines for China's largest
commercial city, have tried to clean up their operations by making
their procedures open to the public.
</P>
<P>
Because they are responsible for working out government prices
for some commodities and approving prices and service charges of
companies, these officials are considered the most vulnerable to
corruption.
</P>
<P>
So, the scope of their work, administrative procedures, and
penalties are now being made more public. They may not use their
routine work for personal benefit, and the receiving of gifts or
purchasing goods at lower prices are strictly banned, and serious
breaches of conduct will be dealt with in accordance with the
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
