<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rural Tourist Spot In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- A county in China's Anhui
Province that is known as the "cradle of China's rural reform" is
becoming a new place for tourists.
</P>
<P>
Fengyang County pioneered the household contract responsibility
system with remuneration linked to output in the late 1970s, at the
beginning of China's reforms, but it wasn't thought of as a
tourist spot until recently.
</P>
<P>
It is also the home of Zhu Yuanzhang, the first emperor of the
Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), and has the Minghuang (Ming Emperor)
Mausoleum of Zhu's parents. Although the site at one time had the
largest imperial tombs in China, they were partly destroyed over
the years, but magnificent roads, exquisite stone tablets, and a
tablet inscription of the emperor remain intact.
</P>
<P>
Although Minghuang City, which was 10,000 sq.m. larger than the
Forbidden City in Beijing, was destroyed, its Wu Gate is protected.
</P>
<P>
Fengyang is known for its 'hua gu' (local singing and dancing)
and the folklore of the Huaihe River. It also has natural lakes
and mountain resorts.
</P>
<P>
To help entice tourists, the county has spent 40 million yuan
(4.8 million US dollars) on its scenic spots and hotels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
