<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's trade surplus in
November rose 58.7 percent over the same period last year to
1,063.7 billion yen (8.4 billion US dollars), the Ministry of
Finance said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the month increased 6.4 percent from a year earlier
to 4,223.8 billion yen. Imports dropped 4.2 percent to 3,160.2
billion yen, the first in 43 months, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus with the United States surged 28.2 percent to
483.9 billion yen. Exports to the U.S. rose 9.4 percent to 1,198.4
billion yen while imports dropped 0.4 percent to 714.5 billion yen.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the European Union (EU) surged 81.6 percent to
280.1 billion yen. Exports to EU countries rose 13.9 percent to
683.3 billion yen while imports fell 9.5 percent to 403.3 billion
yen.
</P>
<P>
While, Japan's exports to the Asian countries dropped 1.9
percent to 1,692.4 billion yen but imports plunged 7.4 percent to
1,137.2 billion yen, leaving a surplus of 555.2 billion yen, up
11.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
