<HEADLINE> Worst in Thai Economy Yet to Come: Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai said on Wednesday that Thailand's economy would start to
recover after four to five months.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on revision of the Eight National Development Plan
(1995-1999), he indicated that the worst times for the economy are
anticipated in the next four to five months, adding that matters
would remain critical for five to six months, particularly if the
country fell short of revenue targets.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation has changed dramatically since the Eighth
National Development Plan was made and now it is a good
opportunity to review strategy and the direction of development
and adopt appropriate guidelines for the rest of the plan period.
</P>
<P>
He urged the people to accept that the path to recovery would
be long and rough and that there was no miracle cure for the
economy, according to the Bangkok Post Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although three cuts have been made in the budget, the
government would still fall short of the targeted 800 billion baht
(16.5 billion U.S. dollars) revenue collection in fiscal 1998,
which ends in September next year.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister called for the promotion of tourism and
exports to pull in foreign exchange. 
</P>
