<HEADLINE> Tosovsky Appointed as Czech Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Czech President Vaclav Havel
formally appointed National Bank President Josef Tosovsky as new
prime minister of the republic Wednesday at the Prague Palace and
authorized him to form a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
This event represents the first change of a head of government
in the Czech Republic after the separation of the Czech and Slovak
Republics into two independent states in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
Following the victory in the election of the Chamber of
Deputies held last June, the Civic Democratic party won the right
to form the cabinet. Vaclav Klaus was appointed prime minister
last July.
</P>
<P>
The Klaus-led government was forced to resign on November 30.
</P>
<P>
For days the Civic Democratic Party, Christian Democratic
Union-Czechoslovak and Civic Democratic Alliance underwent many
rounds of arduous negotiations on the formation of the new cabinet
and, in particular, the selection of a new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the appointment of Tosovsky, who is not
affiliated with any party, was the result of a combined concession
made by the various parties.
</P>
<P>
They said the Tosovsky-led government would possibly serve as a
transitional government. It is probable that it may hold a
parliamentary election ahead of schedule next year.
</P>
<P>
Tosovsky, an economist and financial expert, was born on
September 28, 1950, in the city of Nachod close to the border of
Poland.
</P>
<P>
After graduation from the Department of Foreign Trade of the
Czech Economic College in 1973, Tosovsky has been enaged in the
financial business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
