<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Forge Measures to Rescue Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank and the
Bankers Association of the Philippines have agreed on two measures
aimed at easing the unrest in the country's currency market.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has approved the sale of non-deliverable
short-term dollar forward contracts (NDFs) through commercial
banks to pacify corporate borrowers with unhedged
dollar-denominated obligations, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
NDFs are agreements to buy and sell dollars at a prearranged
price for settlement at a future date and will allow the central
bank to preserve its 9.7 billion US dollar in gross international
reserves.
</P>
<P>
The central bank and the association also agreed to raise 150
million dollars on a daily basis to ensure liquidity in the
Philippine Dealing System, the country's electronic currencies
exchange, and meet the requirements of large dollar users such as
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has agreed to supply two dollars for every one
dollar the association raises to boost the volume of dollars
available for sale in the exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, the central bank plans to sell 100 million
dollars while commercial banks under the association will put in
50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both central bank governor Gabriel Singson and the association
president Deogracias Vistan expressed confidence that the measures
will ease the panic-buying and cause the peso to strengthen in the
coming days.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso Wednesday closed at 39.77 pesos to a dollar
after falling to a historic low of 41.60 pesos against the dollar.
It ended the day at an average of 40.024 pesos to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The peso has fallen about 53 percent against the dollar since
the currency crisis hit the country in early July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
