<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Increases in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Latin American countries
received 73 billion U.S. dollars in foreign investment this year,
a considerable increase over previous years, a U.N study said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Economic Commission for Latin America and the
Caribbean (ECLAC) said that investment increased markedly in the
last quarter due to financial turbulence in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report issued in Santiago, ECLAC said that direct
investment reached an unprecedented 44 billion U.S. dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The influx of Foreign capital hit historic records in Brazil,
Mexico, the Dominican Republic and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
ECLAC said the increase was also stimulated by the countries'
liberalization of laws that regulate the flow of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
This year foreign investment spread rather evenly across the
region, which allowed nine South and Central American countries to
finance their current account deficits, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
