<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Developing More Efficient Irrigation Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 18 (Xinhua) -- A new irrigation technique
has been approved by the Ministry of Water Resources and the Henan
Provincial Academy of Agricultural Sciences and University of
Agriculture as a means of saving water and energy, increasing crop
output, and preventing silting.
</P>
<P>
It uses a pipe made of polyethylene and recycled rubber, with
layers that filter and leak and an outer cover, says one of the
developers. When water pressure is applied, it seeps out of the
tiny holes like sweat.
</P>
<P>
Tests in 17 greenhouses in Jiyuan city, in Henan province,
showed that the technique could increase cucumber output by 67
percent and reduce water use by 50 to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
China has some serious water shortage problems, and the
principal form of irrigation is flood waters, or overhead
sprinklers and canal irrigation, all of which mean an immense
waste of water.
</P>
<P>
One Chinese agronomist has called the new irrigation technique
a revolution in water technology and one that should be used all
over the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
