<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eco-Agriculture Pays off in Three Gorges Reservoir Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Preliminary results have been
achieved in developing eco-agriculture in five villages in the
reservoir area of the Three Gorges Project after three years of
experiment.
</P>
<P>
The villages in central China's Hubei Province and rural areas
of Chongqing municipality suffered from serious soil erosion and
had large tracts of hilly land.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Ministry of Agriculture, the farmers in the
villages began to grow wheat, maize, sweet potatoes and vegetable
on hills with a slope of less than 25 degrees in 1993. They
interplanted peanuts, vegetables and soy beans on mountain sides
with a slope of more than 25 degrees and raise fish and shrimps in
ponds.
</P>
<P>
In courtyards, farmers grow vegetables with manure from
methane-generating pits which use pig's dung as raw material.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the villages' gross output value is estimated at
24.38 million yuan this year, up 15.7 percent from last year. The
per-capita net income of villagers is expected to increase 340
yuan this year to 1,675 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng has described eco-agriculture as an
effective measure to develop the rural economy and protect
environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0317 </DOCNO>
