<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Air Lines Reduce Number of Flights To Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- European airlines plan to
reduce the number of flights to Costa Rica in the coming months
due to the small number of tourists that want to visit that
Central American country, sources reported today.
</P>
<P>
Two German companies -- Condor, a subsidiary of Lufthansa, has
already suspended its flights, while LTU which has a weekly flight
between Dusseldorf and San Jose -- will end its operations to
Costa Rica next April.
</P>
<P>
"We have found certain difficulties in that route," said the
Manager of LTU in Costa Rica. He stressed the lack of tourists who
desire to travel to that destination.
</P>
<P>
Spain`s Iberia airlines will reduce its current number of daily
flights between San Jose and Madrid with a stopover in Miami to
three flights a week by January.
</P>
<P>
Iberia however is also planning to once again increase its
flights to five a week next April but without the Miami stopover.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch KLM is also temporarily suspending flights between
San Jose and Amsterdam by March 26.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, United States` airlines have announced they will
increase their flights from several cities to Costa Rica as a
result of an agreement signed between both governments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
