<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Awards Push Family Planning Through Arts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-two theatrical
programs, featuring Chinese family planning policy, have been
awarded, and three of them will be put on stage in the capital
city this weekend, according to China Daily today.
</P>
<P>
The China Population Culture Award, one of the highest honors
in the areas of population and culture, aims to heighten public
awareness of the family planning and stress the concepts of
sustainable population growth and social and economic development,
Wang Futang, deputy director of the Chinese Population Culture
Promotion Association, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 72 award-winning programs, including dramas, songs and a
variety of folk art forms, expound family planning practices, as
well as charity projects such as Project Hope, and appraise the
good ethics of contemporary Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Sustainable development of the environment and resources is
also one of the hot topics in these programs.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, in the five years since the annual award was
wet up, a total of 376 theatrical programs have won the award,
including dramas, songs, folk art forms, novels, photographs nd
other art works.
</P>
<P>
The booming of literary and artistic programs for family
planning work has played an important role in helping popularize
the concept of late marriage and fewer and better births, said
Yang Kuifu, vice-minister of the State Family Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The country started a family planning policy 17 years ago,
bringing about a 300 million reduction in the number of births.
</P>
<P>
Data from the State Family Planning Commission suggest that the
natural population growth rate in China declined to 10.24 per
thousand last year, one per thousand lower than targeted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nongovernmental Organizations Responsible for Poverty Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan Province in southwest
China has begun to change the practice in which the government is
responsible for poverty relief, and is encouraging nongovernmental
organizations to take over the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Association for Promoting Economic Development
of Poor Townships and Villages, a non-governmental organization,
was founded to push forward the poverty-relief campaign by extending
small loans to poor households.
</P>
<P>
The association has begun to aid the needy in 24 counties, and
plans to do so in all the 63 poor counties of the province in the
coming two years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the UN Development Program (UNDP) has been
undertaking a project of this kind in four counties of Sichuan by
providing small loans directly to poor families.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan, which still has more than five million rural
residents below the poverty line, is following suit. Its new
poverty relief method enables farmers to choose projects and use
funds independently.
</P>
<P>
The association is responsible for extending and recovering the
loans, and providing technical services.
</P>
<P>
The funding mainly comes from government appropriations, bank
loans for poverty relief, donations and earnings of the
association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinotrans Announces Massive Restructuring Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Sinotrans, China's top foreign
trade transportation agent, announced a massive asset
restructuring Wednesday to modernize tis corporate structure,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
It will reorganize its subsidiary companies into a group to
bring their operations in line with China's corporate law.
</P>
<P>
These branches have been under heavy operational and personnel
interference from local government in recent years.
</P>
<P>
China National Foreign Trade Transportation Corp.(Sinotrans)
also announced at a press conference that it will change its name
to China National Foreign Trade Transportation (Group) Corp.
(Sinotrans Group).
</P>
<P>
The group will close some of its outlets to avoid
self-competition, said group Chairman and President Luo Kaifu. In
principle, only one foreign trade transportation outlet will
remain in each of the provinces, municipalities, autonomous
regions and open port cities.
</P>
<P>
Under the new moves, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Co-operation(Moftec)will be defined as the owner of this wholly
State-owned company, with the power to make important business
decisions and choose business executives for the group. Moftec, as
the investor, will enjoy the business yield of the group.
</P>
<P>
Sinotrans, set up in 1950 as a specialized trade transportation
company under the foreign trade ministry, was designated in April
by the State council as one of 120 pilot business groups to
pioneer corporate system reforms.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Sinotrans handles 100 million tons of freight. Its
business turnover in China alone hit 6 billion yuan (about 725.5
million U.S. dollars), generating a pre-tax profit of 340 million
yuan (about 41.4 million U.S.dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
