<HEADLINE> Physical Exams Join Curriculum in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Physical training will become
one of seven major courses that the students in junior high
schools have to complete in order to go to senior high
schools next year in China.
</P>
<P>
The scores in physical exams account for 30 of the total 670
credits, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made during a work conference on China's
physical culture, hygiene and national defence education, held in
Wuhan, capital of Central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The policy was then implemented as a pilot programme in nine
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, including
Beijing, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Since then, more than 70 percent of the students have passed,
according to the State Education Commission (SEC).
</P>
<P>
The programme received wide-ranging approval. Teachers,
students and their families agreed it is an effective way to build
bodies and improve study habits.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 50 million middle school students,
including 800,000 in professional middle school, reveals SEC
statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
