<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Threatens to Block Honduran Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government
reiterated its threat to block Honduran exports worth 5 million
U.S. dollars before Christmas and the new year.
</P>
<P>
Honduran Vice Minister of Foreign Trade Sergio Nunez denounced
the action Wednesday. He said the "Christmas sanctions" may be
enforced because U.S. authorities claim Honduras has not taken the
correct action to protect intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week the National Commission of Telecommunication
took sanctions against the owner of TV station Channel 6 based in
San Pedro Sula, in the north of the country, in violations of copyright
laws.
</P>
<P>
U.S. authorities claim the 150,000 U.S. dollar fine was not
enough to punish the transgression of an international law.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has told us that we have to take energetic
action to protect property rights before Christmas if we want to
avoid sanctions on our exports, and if we are to continue to
operate under the regime of commercial preferences to Central
American and Caribbean countries," explained Nunez.
</P>
<P>
He said it was unfair of the United States to try and correct
Honduras.
</P>
<P>
A better way to solve those issues would be to sign a free trade
agreement with the United States instead of depending upon a
unilateral system of preferences granted by the United States.
</P>
<P>
In the same sense, the Honduran Council of Private Businesses
said the United States uses Honduras as a "scapegoat" before the
world, boasting how hard its measures are when other nations allow
trading in counterfeit intellectual goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971218.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
