<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen said
Wednesday his government opposed a parliamentary proposal that
elections be postponed beyond the May schedule.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's National Assembly (parliament) is considering
postponing the polls by at least two months to allow better
preparation for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said the government insisted that the general elections
be held on May 23 as scheduled. If it was to be put off for
technical problems, it should be no more than one month.
</P>
<P>
But he said it was up to the parliament to make the final
decision. (Cambodia-Hun Sen-Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- At least 35 people were killed Wednesday in two
separate car crashes in South Africa, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
At least 25 people were killed when their bus crashed into a
dried riverbed just outside Queenstown in the Eastern Cape
Province on early Wednesday morning, local police said.
</P>
<P>
The bus apparently left the road and crashed into a deep
riverbed, police said.
</P>
<P>
42 passengers survived the accident, some of whom were
seriously injured. (S. Africa-accidents)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Dozens of injures and heavy damages were reported
in Guam after Typhoon Paka swept through the island with 280 kph
winds before dawn Wednesday local time.
</P>
<P>
Houses, trees, utility poles and glass were flying cross the
whole island when the storm went over Guam. The island's four
major power plants were heavily damaged, leaving most of the its
135,000 residents without electricity.
</P>
<P>
The storm also blew down the equipment that measures wind
speeds for the military's Joint Typhoon Warning Center.
</P>
<P>
A state of emergency was declared and the National Guard was
called out today. (Typhoon-Guam)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A U.S. federal immigration judge has ordered a
former Nazi guard deported from the United States to his homeland,
Slovakia, said reports reaching here from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
Johann Breyer, 72, a retired tool and die maker, was found once
serving as a guard at Auschwitz and Buchenwald Nazi camps during
World War II, an Associated Press report today quoted the Justice
Department as saying Tuesday. (US-Nazi-Deportation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A 25-year-old nurse accused of premediated murder of a
patient and attempted killing of 29 others in a hospital in
Alexandria, Egypt's second largest city, will be tried, the Middle
East News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Aida Noureddin Mohamed was arrested in August on suspicion of
murdering patients at a public hospital in Alexandria over a
six-month period. But the nurse denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
She is also accused of stealing toxic medicines which she
administered to the patients under intensive care in the brain and
nerve center where she worked. (Egypt-Mass Murder)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- A Ukrainian Airlines plane with 71 passengers and
crew on board disappeared on Wednesday evening from radar screens
as it was preparing to land in northern Greece's Macedonia airport.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which was on the route from Kiev and Odessa to
Athens, had asked for permission to land at the airport since 8
p.m. local time, but gave no signal after that, the semi-official
Athens News Agency (ANA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An initial report said that the plane had crashed southwest of
Thessaloniki, the largest city in northern Greece, but this has
not been confirmed. (Greece-Plane) 
</P>
