<HEADLINE> Seminars Boost Fuel Economy in Autos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 18 (Xinhua) -- China's auto sector is
working with General Motors (GM) on possible technical advances to
improve the environment, reduce the emission of greenhouse gases
and prevent the oil crunch, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Jincheng, vice-minister of the Machine-Building Industry
(MMBI), said that the development of energy conserving vehicles
and invention of new substitutes for traditional fuel are crucial
for the survival of the automotive sector.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made at the on-going automotive fuel economy
seminar, which was hosted jointly by General Motors China and
China Automotive Technology and Research Centre under MMBI. It is
the fifth such technology conference held during the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this, GM and MMBI have jointly held four technology
seminars on automotive safety, emissions, testing and unleaded
fuel.
</P>
<P>
"We are formulating policies on fuel economy standards, and
even some rigorous measures, as the necessary means to encourage
application of new technology and expertise," Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
GM will localize the production of engine management systems
until State authorities enforce regulations on the use of clean
fuel sources nationwide. Currently, it plans to supply some engine
parts to the 1.6 billion US dollars Buick project already set up
in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
