<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Economy Up 5.3 Percent in 1997: U.N. Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Latin America and the
Caribbean will enjoy an average economic growth of 5.3 percent in
1997, the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin American
and the Caribbean (ECLAC) reported today.
</P>
<P>
At its annual report "Preliminary Balance of Latin America and
the Caribbean Economy" distributed in Santiago, the ECLAC said
that the region's per capita product in 1997 will rise 3.6 percent
over the previous year and 13 percent over the beginning of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
The document explained that the better current situation is due
essentially to significant improvements in seven countries --
Argentina, Costa Rica, El Salvador, Mexico, Peru, Uruguay and
Venezuela -- and to the outstanding dynamism of Chile and the
Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
It said that no country this year will suffer a setback in its
economic activity, while six countries -- Argentina, Chile,
Mexico, Peru, Dominical Republic and Uruguay -- will have a growth
of 6 to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Only three nations -- Haiti, Jamaica and Santa Lucia -- will
endure stagnation or poor growth in the year, according the
document.
</P>
<P>
The ECLAC indicated that the 1996-1997 growth, in general, was
fed by investment dynamism, which outstripped considerably the
expansion of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in the region.
</P>
<P>
Investment in the region will account for 24 percent of the
GDP, the highest rate for the decade, the document said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign capital inflows were particularly high this year in
Argentina, Bolivia, Costa Rica, Mexico, Nicaragua, Dominican
Republic and Venezuela, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
