<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Closes 1997 With 11-Percent Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Latin America and the
Caribbean will close the year with an average inflation rate of 11
percent, the lowest in 50 years, the United Nations Economic
Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean (ECLAC) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In an annual report entitled "Preliminary Balance of Latin
America and the Caribbean Economy in 1997," the U.N. agency said
that 13 out of 22 Latin American nations registered this year an
inflation rate below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
In most countries, the rate of price increases slowed down. In
Barbados, Ecuador, Haiti and the Dominican Republic, inflation
boosted in the year, but only by less than 10 percent, the ECLAC
said in the report, which was distributed in Santiago today.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that Venezuela reduced considerably its
inflation rate in 1997 to 38 percent, from a previous high of 103
percent. Venezuela still has the highest inflation of the region.
</P>
<P>
The best results were from Argentina, which did not register
any inflation in the year, according to the ECLAC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
