<HEADLINE> USOC Names Sampras as Sportsman of the Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras, who ended the
season as the world's top-ranked tennis player for a fifth
consecutive year, was named Sportsman of the Year on Wednesday by
the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
Sampras claimed the honor with 400 points over hurdler Allen
Johnson, who was second with 376 and third-place figure skater
Todd Eldredge, who got 315 points from a vote by the USOC Board of
Directors, the Athletes' Advisory Council and members of the
national media.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Sampras became the first tennis player to win
the award. He won his second Australian Open title in January and
his fourth Wimbledon crown in July for his 10th career Grand Slam
singles triumph.
</P>
<P>
Sampras was the Athlete of the Year for the United States
Tennis Association in 1994, 1995 and 1997. He has won 52 career
singles titles and two career doubles titles.
</P>
<P>
He will be honored, along with the 1997 Sportswoman of the
Year, figure skater Tara Lipinski, and the Team of the Year, at
the USOC Board of Directors meeting on Saturday, April 4, 1998 in
Portland, Oregon.
</P>
<P>
Athlete Michael Johnson won the honor of Sportsman of the Year
in the last two consecutive years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
