<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Affects NZ Business Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 18 (Xinhua) -- Business confidence in New
Zealand still remains marginally positive this month, although it
"withered" because of the deepening Asian crisis, a latest survey
found.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by the National Bank showed that those
expecting conditions to improve in next year still outnumbered
pessimists by a net 6 percent, a local press report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the margin was down dramatically from a net 26 percent only
a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The fall in confidence is widespread. "Every sector feels less
confident," said National Bank chief economist Brendan O'Donovan.
</P>
<P>
He said confidence held up surprisingly well in November
despite bad news. However, the situation turned around when South
Korea, NZ's fifth biggest export market, "went broke," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the Asian slowdown would mean lower commodity
prices rather than lower volumes. Survey respondents said that
their planned exports for next year were only down slightly, but
profit expectations had been hit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
