<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees Iran's Nuanced Change in Mideast Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday called the Iranian President's remark on the Middle
East peace process a "nuanced change" in a positive direction.
</P>
<P>
"It may be a nuanced change in a positive direction," State
Department spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's
comment at a news conference on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Khatami reiterated Iran's stand on the Middle East peace
process at the news conference, saying it was "not just."
</P>
<P>
But he went on to say: "Of course, we have vigorously stated
that we never seek to impose the Islamic Republic of Iran's views
on others. They have their own understanding and going ahead."
</P>
<P>
Foley said it was "a rhetorical nuance that represents
language that we haven't heard ... and in that sense, it is
positive."
</P>
<P>
However, Foley accused Iran of taking actions in "support for
terrorism and violent opposition to the Middle East peace
process," and he said the United States was looking for Iran's
"change in actions." 
</P>
