<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Aid to Go to Bosnian Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that it will try to ensure that a World Bank loan to
Bosnia's Serb Republic goes mostly to people who support the
Dayton peace accords.
</P>
<P>
"What we are proposing now is to target assistance to those who
have demonstrated a willingness to implement Dayton, and we
believe that it is vital that cooperation of this sort be
rewarded," State Department spokesman James Foley said.
</P>
<P>
About 85 percent of the 17 million U.S. dollars would go to the
town of Brcko and the western part of the Serb Republic, which is
mostly under the control of President Biljana Plavsic, the Bosnian
Serb favored by Washington.
</P>
<P>
Foley said that only 15 percent would go to the east of the
republic, where hard-liner Radovan Karadzic and other opponents of
Dayton exert influence from their base in the town of Pale.
</P>
<P>
"In some cases (it will go to) the cities that are under Pale's
influence," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"This will be for humanitarian support to repair water and
sewer systems in areas where there are large numbers of refugees,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Department has told Congress that the United
States is likely to vote for this loan, according to Foley. The
vote has been postponed by the World Bank until December 23.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank originally set a vote on the loan for December
2, but postponed it until Bosnia settled some arrears to the
International Monetary Fund (IMF). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
