<HEADLINE> Gene for Longer-Lasting Tomatoes Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at the
University of California, Davis, have found one of the genes that
allows fruit skins to expand during the ripening process.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from The Futurist, the gene controls
expansions, proteins that allow fruit to grow, but also let fruit
soften quickly after ripening. Researchers said knowing how these
genes work is a step toward controlling them.
</P>
<P>
Although a genetically engineered tomato exists today, the
report said, this discovery could lead to a new engineering
process that allows longer shelf lives for ripe fruit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
