<HEADLINE> Blair Pledges to Continue Efforts on N.Ireland Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair pledged today to stand by the troubled Northern Ireland
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Talking not fighting is the only way to achieve a settlement,"
said Blair, who was on a brief Christmas goodwill visit to the
British province.
</P>
<P>
He also said he would do everything he possibly could to bring
about a lasting political settlement to the Northern Ireland
problems.
</P>
<P>
"The only way we are going to get a lasting political
settlement is if people are talking to one another rather than
fighting one another. We will do whatever we can to move it (the
peace process) forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the failure to reach an agreement Tuesday by the two
major rival parties in Northern Ireland, Blair said he was still
optimistic that progress would be achieved in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
"I think that in the New Year, perhaps after we have had the
Christmas break, that we are able to move the thing on to get
progress, not just on an agenda but heads of agreement.... I still
remain cautiously, very cautiously optimistic that we can do it,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
